70720220054/https://berniesanders.com/democratic-socialism-in-the-united-states/|archivedate=July 20, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* Vice President [[Joe Biden]] (born 1942), Democratic Vice President from 2009 to 2017<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/3319325/joe-biden-violence-against-women/|title=20 Years of Change: Joe Biden on the Violence Against Women Act|work=Time|accessdate=March 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* Senator [[Paul Wellstone]] (1944\u20132002), Democrat from Minnesota<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/peter-dreier/paul-wellstones-life-and-_1_b_8383662.html|title=Paul Wellstone's Ordinary Life and Extraordinary Legacy|last=Dreier|first=Peter|work=The Huffington Post|accessdate=April 10, 2018}}</ref>\n* Representative [[Dennis Kucinich]] (born 1946), Ohio, Democrat\n* President [[Bill Clinton]] (born 1946), Democratic President from 1993 to 2001\n* Secretary [[Hillary Clinton]] (born 1947), Secretary of State from 2009 to 2013 and 2016 Democratic presidential nominee\n* Governor [[Howard Dean]] (born 1948), Democrat from Vermont<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/3080558/ns/msnbc-buchanan_and_press/t/howard-dean-too-liberal/#.WsWLYiOZNAY|title=Is Howard Dean too liberal?|publisher=NBC News|date=August 12, 2004|accessdate=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* Senator [[Elizabeth Warren]] (born 1949), Democrat from Massachusetts\n* Senator [[Russ Feingold]] (born 1953), Democrat from Wisconsin\n* Senator [[Amy Klobuchar]] (born 1960), Democrat from Minnesota\n* Congressman [[Beto O'Rourke]] (born 1972), Democrat from Texas\n* President [[Barack Obama]] (born 1961), Democratic President from 2009 to 2017\n* Mayor [[Pete Buttigieg]] (born 1982), Democrat from Indiana\n\n; Intellectuals\n* [[Lester Frank Ward]] (1841\u20131913), sociologist\n* [[Thorstein Veblen]] (1857\u20131929), economist\n* [[John Dewey]] (1859\u20131952), philosopher\n* [[Herbert Croly]] (1869\u20131930), political scientist\n* [[Vernon Louis Parrington]] (1871\u20131929), historian\n* [[Charles A. Beard]] (1874\u20131948), historian\n* [[Alvin Hansen]] (1887\u20131975), economist\n* [[Reinhold Niebuhr]] (1892\u20131971), theologian\n* [[Henry Steele Commager]] (1902\u20131998), historian<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.historians.org/publications-and-directories/perspectives-on-history/may-1998/in-memoriam-henry-steele-commager|title=In Memoriam: Henry Steele Commager (1902-98)|publisher=American Historical Association|accessdate=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Lionel Trilling]] (1905\u20131975), literary critic\n* [[John Kenneth Galbraith]] (1908\u20132006), economist\n* [[C. Vann Woodward]] (1908\u20131999), historian\n* [[Alfred Kazin]] (1915\u20131998), literary critic and writer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/96704/kazin-journals-criticism-literature-america|title=The Inner Clamor|last=Kirsch|first=Adam|publisher=The New Republic|date=October 26, 2011|accessdate=March 13, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Richard Hofstadter]] (1916\u20131970), historian\n* [[Eric F. Goldman]] (1916\u20131989), historian\n* [[Arthur Schlesinger Jr.]] (1917\u20132007), historian\n* [[John Rawls]] (1921\u20132002), philosopher\n* [[William Appleman Williams]] (1921\u20131990), historian\n* [[Richard Rorty]] (1931\u20132007), philosopher\n* [[Garry Wills]] (born 1934), historian\n* [[Robert Reich]] (born 1946), economist\n* [[Roberto Unger]] (born 1947), philosopher\n* [[Amy Gutmann]] (born 1949), political scientist\n* [[Henry Louis Gates]] (born 1950), historian\n* [[Paul Krugman]] (born 1953), economist\n* [[Melissa Harris-Perry]] (born 1972), African-American scholar\n\n; Jurists and the law\n* Justice [[Louis Brandeis]] (1856\u20131941)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thepublicdiscourse.com/2016/01/16324/|title=Justice Brandeis and the Birth of Liberal Judicial Activism|website=Thepublicdiscourse.com|accessdate=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n* Justice [[Felix Frankfurter]] (1882\u20131965)\n* Chief Justice [[Earl Warren]] (1891\u20131974)\n* Justice [[William O. Douglas]] (1898\u20131980)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/politics/1980/01/20/william-o-douglas-dies-at-81/75701707-7e27-4414-95ee-220ec5f77dbe/|title=William O. Douglas Dies at 81|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|last=Rich|first=Spencer|date=January 20, 1980|accessdate=April 15, 2018}}</ref>\n* Justice [[William J. Brennan Jr.]] (1906\u20131997)\n* Justice [[Thurgood Marshall]] (1908\u20131993)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://constitutioncenter.org/blog/thurgood-marshalls-unique-supreme-court-legacy|title=Thurgood Marshall's Unique Supreme Court Legacy|publisher=Constitution Daily|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n* Judge [[A. Leon Higginbotham Jr.]] (1928\u20131998)\n* [[Ronald Dworkin]] (1931\u20132013), jurisprudence\n* [[John Hart Ely]] (1938\u20132003), jurisprudence\n* [[Laurence Tribe]] (born 1941), jurisprudence\n* [[Harold Koh]] (born 1954), jurisprudence\n* [[Pamela Karlan]] (born 1959), jurisprudence\n* [[Jeffrey Toobin]] (born 1960), lawyer, legal analyst and author\n{{col-break}}\n\n; Writers, activists and commentators\n* [[Samuel Gompers]] (1850\u20131924), labor leader, founder and first president of the [[American Federation of Labor]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notablebiographies.com/Gi-He/Gompers-Samuel.html|title=Samuel Gompers Biography|website=Notablebiographies.com|accessdate=March 18, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Jane Addams]] (1860-1935), social worker and activist\n* [[W.E.B. DuBois]] (1868\u20131963), Black leader<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.keyreporter.org/PbkNews/PbkNews/Details/1236.html|title=W.E.B. DuBois on the Value of Liberal Education|website=Keyreporter.org|accessdate=February 13, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[William Monroe Trotter]] (1872\u20131934), civil rights leader and founder of the ''[[Boston Guardian]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpast.org/aah/trotter-william-monroe-1872-1934|title=William Monroe Trotter|website=Blackpast.org|accessdate=March 11, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Edith Abbott]] (1876\u20131957), economist and social worker\n* [[Eleanor Roosevelt]] (1884\u20131962), writer, Democratic leader, First Lady from 1933 to 1945 and wife of [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]\n* [[A. Philip Randolph]] (1889\u20131979), notable leader in [[American labor movement]] and [[civil rights movement]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/A-Philip-Randolph|title=A. Philip Randolph|publisher=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]]|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Rachel Carson]] (1907\u20131964), environmentalist \n* [[Walter Reuther]] (1907\u20131970), leader in [[American labor movement]] and [[civil rights movement]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://aflcio.org/about/history/labor-history-people/walter-reuther|title=Walter Reuther|publisher=AFL-CIO|accessdate=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Fannie Lou Hamer]] (1917\u20131977), [[Voting rights|voting]] and [[civil rights]] activist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mshistorynow.mdah.state.ms.us/articles/51/fannie-lou-hamer-civil-rights-activist|title=Fannie Lou Hamer: Civil Rights Activist|publisher=Mississippi History Now|accessdate=March 9, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Betty Friedan]] (1921\u20132006), feminist and first president of the [[National Organization for Women]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Celebrating Our Presidents|url=http://www.now.org/history/past_presidents.html|publisher=National Organization for Women|accessdate=March 6, 2018|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100121153357/http://www.now.org/history/past_presidents.html|archivedate=January 21, 2010|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[Gore Vidal]] (1925\u20132012), author\n* [[Coretta Scott King]] (1927\u20132006), Black leader\n* [[Cesar Ch\u00e1vez]] (1927\u20131993), Chicano leader\n* [[Harvey Milk]] (1930\u20131978), gay rights activist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.legacyprojectchicago.org/Harvey_Milk.html|title=Harvey Milk|accessdate=March 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Betty Ford]] (1918\u20132011), First Lady from 1974 to 1977, feminist and women's rights activist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,912914,00.html|title=Women: A Fighting First Lady|publisher=Time Magazine|accessdate=March 7, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[George Soros]] (born 1930), financier and philanthropist\n* [[Susan Sontag]] (1933\u20132004), writer<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/12/11/the-other-susan-sontag|title=The Other Susan Sontag|last=Haslett|first=Tobi|newspaper=[[The New Yorker]]|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=March 21, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Gloria Steinem]] (born 1934), feminist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/gloria-steinem-9493491|title=Gloria Steinem|website=Biography.com|accessdate=March 5, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Bill Moyers]] (born 1934), journalist and political commentator\n* [[Bill Press]] (born 1940), journalist and political commentator\n* [[Jim Hightower]] (born 1943), columnist, author and activist\n* [[Faye Wattleton]] (born 1943), feminist\n* [[James Carville]] (born 1944), political commentator\n* [[Patricia Ireland]] (born 1945), feminist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://biography.yourdictionary.com/patricia-ireland|title=Patricia Ireland|website=Biography.yourdictionary.com|accessdate=March 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Alan Colmes]] (1950\u20132017), political commentator\n* [[Arianna Huffington]] (born 1950), political commentator\n* [[Lawrence O'Donnell]] (born 1951), political commentator\n* [[Michael Moore]] (born 1954), filmmaker\n* [[Bill Maher]] (born 1956), comedian and political commentator\n* [[Keith Olbermann]] (born 1959), journalist and political commentator\n* [[Katrina vanden Heuvel]] (born 1959), journalist and political commentator\n* [[Tavis Smiley]] (born 1964), political commentator\n* [[Cenk Uygur]] (born 1970), radio host and political commentator\n* [[Rachel Maddow]] (born 1973), political commentator<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/biography/Rachel-Maddow|title=Rachel Maddow: American Political Commentator|publisher=[[Encyclopedia Britannica]]|accessdate=April 9, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Shaun King]] (born 1979), civil rights activist\n* [[Linda Sarsour]] (born 1980), civil rights activist\n* [[Matthew Yglesias]] (born 1981), blogger and journalist\n* [[Dena Takruri]] (born 1983), journalist and reporter\n* [[Ezra Klein]] (born 1984), columnist and blogger\n* [[Ana Kasparian]] (born 1986), political commentator\n\n; Religious leaders\n* [[Anna Pauline Murray]] (1910\u20131985), minister, lawyer and civil rights activist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2017/04/17/the-many-lives-of-pauli-murray|title=The Many Lives of Pauli Murray|last=Schulz|first=Kathryn|publisher=[[The New Yorker]]|date=April 4, 2017|accessdate=March 16, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] (1929\u20131968) minister and civil rights activist\n* [[Arthur Waskow]] (born 1933), rabbi, political activist and author\n* [[Jesse Jackson]] (born 1941), minister and civil rights activist\n* [[Michael Lerner (rabbi)|Michael Lerner]] (born 1943), rabbi and political activist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tikkun.org/rabbi_lerner/bio|title=Biographical Notes on Rabbi Lerner|accessdate=March 18, 2018|url-status=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080107085329/http://www.tikkun.org/rabbi_lerner/bio|archivedate=January 7, 2008|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[David Saperstein (rabbi)|David Saperstein]] (born 1947) rabbi and political activist\n* [[Jim Wallis]] (born 1948), evangelical pastor, founder and editor of ''[[Sojourners]]''\n* [[Al Sharpton]] (born 1954), minister and civil rights activist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://thegrio.com/2013/03/28/black-america-doesnt-lack-leaders/|title=Black America doesn't lack leaders: Poll shows 24 percent say Sharpton speaks for them|publisher=The Grio|date=March 28, 2013|accessdate=March 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Lennox Yearwood]] (born 1969), minister and activist\n* [[State of Belief|Welton Gaddy]], minister, religious commentator and radio host\n\n; Blogs\n* [[AlterNet]]\n* [[Daily Kos]]\n* [[FireDogLake]]\n* [[The Huffington Post]]\n* [[Talking Points Memo]]\n* [[Salon.com|Salon]]\n* [[ThinkProgress]]\n\n; Magazines and publications\n* ''[[The American Prospect]]''\n* ''[[The Atlantic]]''\n* ''[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]]''\n* ''[[The Nation]]''\n* ''[[The New Republic]]''\n* ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n* ''[[Sojourners]]''\n\n; Think tanks\n* [[Center for American Progress]]\n* [[Roosevelt Institute]]\n* [[Center on Budget and Policy Priorities]]\n{{col-break}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Conservatism in the United States]]\n* [[Economic interventionism]]\n* [[Progressive Christianity]]\n* [[Progressive talk radio]]\n* [[Progressivism in the United States]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{refbegin|colwidth=60em}}\n* Abrams, Richard M. ''America Transformed: Sixty Years of Revolutionary Change, 1941\u20132001'' (2006)\n* Alterman, Eric, and Kevin Mattson. ''The Cause: The Fight for American Liberalism from Franklin Roosevelt to Barack Obama'' (2012) biographical approach to general survey [https://www.amazon.com/The-Cause-American-Liberalism-Roosevelt/dp/0670023434/  excerpt and text search]\n* Battista, Andrew. ''The Revival of Labor Liberalism'' (2008) 268 pp.&nbsp;{{ISBN|978-0-252-03232-5}}\n* Bell, Jonathan and Timothy Stanley, eds. ''Making Sense of American Liberalism'' (2012) 272pp [https://www.amazon.com/gp/reader/0252036867/  excerpt and text search], 10 historical essays by experts\n* Boyle, Kevin. ''The UAW and the Heyday of American Liberalism 1945\u20131968'' (1995) on the [[UAW]] (auto workers)\n* Brands, H. W. ''The Strange Death of American Liberalism'' (2003); brief survey of all of American history.\n* Conn, Steven, ed. ''To Promote the General Welfare: The Case for Big Government''  (Oxford University Press; 2012) 233 pages;\n* Cronin, James, George Ross, and James Shoch, eds. ''What's Left of the Left: Democrats and Social Democrats in Challenging Times'' (Duke University Press