s, Paul L. ''The Politics of Selfishness: How John Locke's Legacy is Paralzying America.'' (Praeger, 2010)\n* Parker, Richard. ''John Kenneth Galbraith: His Life, His Politics, His Economics'' (2006); biography of a leading intellectual of 1940s-1960s\n* Rossinow, Doug.  ''Visions of Progress: The Left-Liberal Tradition in America'' (2008)\n* Starr. Paul. ''Freedom's Power: The History and Promise of Liberalism'' (2007), by a leading liberal scholar\n*  Stein,  Herbert. ''Presidential Economics: The Making of Economic Policy From Roosevelt to Clinton'' (3rd ed. 1994)\n* Sugrue, Thomas J. ''Sweet Land of Liberty: The Forgotten Struggle for Civil Rights in the North'' (2009)\n* Willard, Charles Arthur. ''Liberalism and the Problem of Knowledge: A New Rhetoric for Modern Democracy'' (1996); debunks liberalism, arguing that its exaggerated ideals of authenticity, unity, and community have deflected attention from the pervasive incompetence of \"the rule of experts.\"\n* Wilentz, Sean. ''The Age of Reagan: A History, 1974\u20132008'' (2008), by a leading liberal.\n\n{{refend}}\n{{leftism in the United States}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:United States}}\n[[Category:Liberalism in the United States| ]]\n[[Category:Liberalism]]\n[[Category:Social liberalism]]\n[[Category:Politics of the United States|Modern liberalism]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo(s) fixed: Vice President \u2192 vice president (5), President \u2192 president (10); sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modern_liberalism_in_the_United_States"}
{"title_page": "Jon Ossoff", "text_new": "{{short description|Democratic nominee for Congress in the 2017 special election}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox politician\n|name = Jon Ossoff\n|image = Ossoff-Mar-15-17.png\n|birth_name = Thomas Jonathan Ossoff\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|2|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education = [[Georgetown University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[London School of Economics]]<br>([[Master of Science|MS]])\n|website = {{url|electjon.com|Campaign website}}\n}}\n'''Thomas Jonathan Ossoff''' (born February 16, 1987)<ref name=\":6\">Mr. Thomas Jonathan Ossoff, Insight Twi Limited; [http://directors.findthecompany.co.uk/l/8809030/Mr-Thomas-Jonathan-Ossoff findthecompany.co.uk] (subscription required)</ref> is an American media executive, investigative journalist,<ref name=\"AJC 2020\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/politics/georgia-senate-ossoff-nets-another-ends-quarter-with-hand/xR53pjf70RyulxACa30UEL/ |title=Georgia Senate: Ossoff nets another $1M, ends quarter with $1.8M on hand |last=Bluestein |first=Greg |date=April 15, 2020 |work=The Atlanta-Journal Constitution |access-date=April 17, 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  and activist.\n\nSince 2013, Ossoff has served as managing director and CEO of Insight TWI, a multi-Emmy award winning investigative television production company that produces investigations for news channels around the world. <ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2020/politics/news/jon-ossoff-senate-georgia-1203522791/ |title=Doc Producer Jon Ossoff on His Run for a U.S. Senate Seat in Georgia |last=Ravindran |first=Manori |date=March 5, 2020 |work=Variety |access-date=April 17, 2020 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n \nOssoff was the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee for Congress in the historically expensive [[Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017|2017 special election]] in [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]]; he lost with 48.2% of the vote to Republican [[Karen Handel]]'s 51.8%.<ref name=\"insights-twi\">{{cite web|url=https://insighttwi.com/contact|title=Insight TWI: The World Investigates}}</ref><ref name=\"Hefty-Advantages-AJC\">{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/01/05/another-democrat-announces-for-tom-prices-seat-with-some-hefty-advantages|title=A Democrat with a pile of cash commitments announces for Tom Price's seat|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=February 20, 2017|last=Bluestein|first=Greg}}</ref><ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=About Jon|url=https://electjon.com/about-jon/|publisher=Jon Ossoff for Congress|year=2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Barrow\">{{cite web|author=Bill Barrow|url=https://elections.ap.org/content/georgia-special-election-shapes-referendum-trump|title=Georgia special election shapes up as referendum on Trump|date=February 14, 2017|work=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nOssoff is running in the Democratic primary for the [[2020 United States Senate election in Georgia |2020 Georgia Senate election]] against Republican incumbent Senator [[David Perdue]].<ref name=\"NYT 2020\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/09/us/politics/jon-ossoff-2020-georgia-senate.html |title=Jon Ossoff Will Run for Senate in Georgia |last=Astor |first=Maggie |date=September 9, 2019 |work=The New York Times |access-date=September 10, 2019 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nOssoff was born on February 16, 1987,<ref name=\":6\" /> in [[Atlanta]], Georgia. He was raised in [[Northlake, Georgia|Northlake]], an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]].<ref name=\"electjon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://electjon.com/news/2017/1/4/jon-ossoff-announces-congressional-bid-in-georgia|title=Jon Ossoff Announces Congressional Bid|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222084607/https://electjon.com/news/2017/1/4/jon-ossoff-announces-congressional-bid-in-georgia|archivedate=February 22, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff attended the [[The Paideia School|Paideia School]], a small private school in Atlanta.<ref name=\":0\" /> While in high school, he interned for Georgia congressman and civil rights leader [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2009, Ossoff graduated from [[Georgetown University]]'s [[School of Foreign Service]] with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree. He attended classes taught by former [[List of Secretaries of State of the United States|secretary of state]] [[Madeleine Albright]] and former [[List of Israeli ambassadors to the United States|Israeli ambassador to the United States]] [[Michael Oren]].<ref name=\"wp-2017-02-23\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/daily-202/2017/02/23/daily-202-will-anti-trump-backlash-let-democrats-win-the-georgia-special-election-to-replace-tom-price/58ae458be9b69b1406c75ceb/|title=The Daily 202: Will anti-Trump backlash let Democrats win the Georgia special election to replace Tom Price?|last=Hohmann|first=James|date=February 23, 2017|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref name=\"db-2017-03-01\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2017/02/27/could-the-resistance-start-with-georgia-s-special-election.html|title=Could The Resistance Start With Georgia's Special Election?|last=Murphy|first=Patricia|date=February 27, 2017|work=Daily Beast|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff went on to earn his [[Master of Science]] degree from [[London School of Economics]] in 2013.<ref name=\"wp-2017-02-23\" /><ref name=\"db-2017-03-01\" />\n\n== Political career ==\nOssoff worked as a national security staffer and aide to Rep. [[Hank Johnson]] for five years during which he drafted and managed legislative initiatives that passed the House and [[United States Senate|Senate]].<ref name=\"electjon.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2017/apr/03/jon-ossoff/jon-ossoff-national-security-background/|title=How extensive was Jon Ossoff's national security background?|work=@politifact|access-date=April 6, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He had [[Security clearance#Top Secret|top-secret clearance]] for five months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/326800-democrats-go-for-broke-in-race-for-tom-prices-seat|title=Democrats go for broke in race for Tom Price's seat|last=Weaver|first=Dustin|date=April 1, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Since 2013, he has been managing partner and [[CEO]] of Insight TWI, a small business based in the United Kingdom<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insighttwi.com/contact.html |title=Contact Us &#124; Insight TWI: The World Investigates |publisher=Insight TWI |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> which produces investigations targeting corrupt officials and [[organized crime]] for international news organizations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/no-blood-diamonds-or-gunrunning-in-sight-why-the-documentary-film-sierra-leone-an-artist-s-journey-a7311421.html|title=No Blood Diamonds or Gunrunning in Sight, Why the Documentary Film?|work=Independent|date=September 16, 2016|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> In 2016, Ossoff was an executive producer for a documentary film by Insight TWI for [[BBC Three]]; the film exposed atrocities committed by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL in Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insighttwi.com/films/girlsgunsisis|accessdate=February 23, 2017|title=Girls, Guns and Isis|publisher=Insight TWI, Ltd.}}</ref>\n\n===2017 special election===\n{{main|Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017}}\n\nAfter learning that [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]] of Georgia's 6th district had been appointed secretary of Health and Human Services, Ossoff announced his candidacy for this [[Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017|special election]] on January 5, 2017.<ref name=\"db-2017-03-01\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/01/05/another-democrat-announces-for-tom-prices-seat-with-some-hefty-advantages/|title=A Democrat with a pile of cash commitments announces for Tom Price's seat|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=January 5, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff quickly emerged as the most viable Democratic candidate out of a large field of candidates.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ed Kilgore|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/02/georgia-special-house-election-still-gops-race-to-lose.html|title=Georgia's Special Election to Replace Tom Price Is Still the GOP's Race to Lose|date=February 16, 2017|magazine=New York}}</ref> He was endorsed by prominent figures such as Congressmen [[Hank Johnson]] and [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]],<ref name=\"Barrow\"/><ref name=\"mh-2017-02-23\">{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article134490239.html|title=Democrats hope Trump backlash begins in this ruby-red House seat|last=Roarty|first=Alex|date=February 23, 2017|work=The Miami Herald|accessdate=February 25, 2017}}</ref> and [[Georgia House of Representatives|state House]] Democratic Leader [[Stacey Abrams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/02/09/democrat-aiming-for-tom-prices-seat-picks-up-key-supporter/|title=Democrat aiming for Tom Price's seat picks up key supporter|date=February 9, 2017|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref><ref name=\"wx-2017-03-01\">{{cite news |url=http://www.11alive.com/news/politics/elections/race-to-replace-price-leading-in-polls-ossoff-doesnt-live-in-district/414685623|title=Race to replace Price: Leading in polls, Ossoff doesn't live in district|last=Darnell|first=Tim|publisher=WXIA|date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> He also received public support from Vermont Senator and 2016 Democratic presidential candidate [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/329927-sanders-endorses-ossoff-but-wont-call-him-a-progressive|title=Sanders endorses Ossoff, but won't call him a progressive|first=Will|last=Sommer|date=April 21, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/democrats-reload-for-georgia-runoff-but-party-divisions-remain-1492626238|title=Democrats Reload for Georgia Runoff, But Party Divisions Remain|first1=Reid J.|last1=Epstein|first2=Natalie|last2=Andrews|date=April 19, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 24, 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/democrats-vs-trump/bernie-sanders-clarifies-support-jon-ossoff-after-dustup-n749491|title=Sanders clarifies support for Ossoff after dustup|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref> Ossoff raised over $8.3 million by early April of that year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.myajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/ossoff-pulls-record-donations-for-georgia-special-election/MqGzLMjrzVRR8jE5YGs3rL/|title=Democrat Ossoff rakes in huge amount in 6th District race|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=April 6, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'', Ossoff \"transformed what was expected to be a quiet battle for a long-safe Republican seat into a proxy fight over Trump, the health care overhaul and the partisan struggle for suburbia.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/handel-preps-another-6th-district-campaign-ossoff-hints-comeback/PsDYoQhTSRIsq6myncmmuO/|title=Handel preps another 6th District campaign as Ossoff hints at comeback|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref> When Ossoff entered the race, the [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] rated [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]] at R+14;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170617193745/http://cookpolitical.com/file/2013-04-49.pdf |title=Wayback Machine |publisher=Web.archive.org |date= |accessdate=April 17, 2020}}</ref> the district was not considered competitive, and had been represented in Congress by Republicans since 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/04/georgia-sixth-congressional-district-last-most-recent-democrat-jon-ossoff/|title=When Was the Last Time a Democrat Represented Georgia\u2019s Sixth Congressional District?}}</ref> Less than two months before Ossoff\u2019s announcement, Republican Congressman Tom Price had been re-elected in a landslide with 62% of the vote.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/georgia-house-district-6-price-stooksbury|title=Georgia U.S. House 6th District Results: Tom Price Wins}}</ref>\n\nOssoff grew up in the 6th district, where his family still resides, although as of the election he lived about {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} outside the district's boundaries. As a result, he was unable to vote for himself in the primary. He has said that he temporarily lives in the neighboring 4th District so that his fianc\u00e9e, an [[Emory University School of Medicine|Emory University medical student]], can walk to the hospital where she works. Ossoff says he intends to move back to the 6th district after his fianc\u00e9e completes her medical studies.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/18/politics/georgia-candidate-shrugs-off-district-issues-cnntv/index.html|title=Dem hopeful dismisses questions about residency|authors=Josiah Ryan|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"db-2017-03-01\" /><ref>Robert Costa, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/georgia-house-race-stokes-gop-identity-crisis--and-opportunity-for-democrats/2017/04/18/a2231a48-242f-11e7-b503-9d616bd5a305_story.html \"Republicans avoid big loss by forcing runoff in Ga. House race\"], ''The Washington Post'', April 18, 2017.</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2017, no candidate received 50% of the vote in the [[nonpartisan blanket primary|blanket primary]] (\"jungle primary\").<ref name=CNNShort>{{cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/18/politics/georgia-house-6th-special-election-jon-ossoff/index.html|title=Ossoff falls just short in Georgia special election|first=Eric |last=Bradner|publisher=CNN|access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff led with about 48.1% of the vote, Republican candidate [[Karen Handel]] received 19.8%, while the remainder of votes were scattered for 16 other candidates.<ref name=\"GASOS04192017\">{{cite news |date=April 19, 2017 |title=Unofficial Results |url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/67317/Web02-state/#/ |publisher=Georgia Secretary of State |location=Atlanta, Georgia |access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTApril\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/georgia-house-special-election-district-6|title=Election Results: Ossoff, Handel Advance in Race for Georgia's Sixth Congressional District |work=The New York Times|date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Because no candidate secured an absolute majority, the top two vote-getters, Ossoff and Handel, competed in a [[runoff election]] on June 20, 2017.<ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\"NYTApril\"/> Ossoff won all but 1% of the Democratic vote, while the Republican vote was more heavily split. Republicans collectively won 51.2% of the overall vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/04/ossoff-to-face-handel-in-georgia-special-election-runoff.html|title=Ossoff Falls Short of a Majority in Georgia House Race, Heads to Runoff|first=Ed|last=Kilgore|work=New York|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOssoff broke national fundraising records for a [[U.S. House]] candidate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/09/us/politics/ossoff-handel-georgia-house-special-election.html?mcubz=0|title=Ossoff Raises $23 Million in Most Expensive House Race in History|website=The New York Times|access-date=July 13, 2017}}</ref> In total, Ossoff's campaign raised more than $23 million, two-thirds of which was contributed by small-dollar donors nationwide.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/story/ossoff-social-media-campaign/|title=JON OSSOFF, THE CONGRESSIONAL CANDIDATE SOCIAL MEDIA BUILT|website=Wired|access-date=July 13, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff's opponent, Handel, and national Republican groups attacked Ossoff for raising significant small-dollar contributions from outside of Georgia, although Handel's campaign received the bulk of its support from super PACs and other outside groups, including those funded anonymously by so-called \"[[dark money]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2017/jun/08/ga-6-race-fact-checking-attacks-campaign-cash/|title=In GA-6 race, fact-checking attacks about campaign cash|website=Politifact|access-date=July 13, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/6/19/15827686/georgia-election-ossoff-money|title=Guess who's funding multimillion-dollar ad blitzes slamming Ossoff's out-of-state donors?|website=Vox|access-date=July 13, 2017}}</ref> Combined spending by the campaigns and outside groups on their behalf added up to over $55 million, which was the most expensive House Congressional election in U.S. history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/06/20/us/politics/georgia-6th-most-expensive-house-election.html|title=Who Financed the Georgia Sixth, the Most Expensive House Election Ever|last=Parlapiano|first=Alicia|date=June 20, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 23, 2017|last2=Shorey|first2=Rachel|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During the campaign, Republican strategy focused on connecting Ossoff to House Democratic Leader [[Nancy Pelosi]], a polarizing and unpopular figure amongst Republicans; Ossoff declined to say whether he would, if elected, support Pelosi for Speaker of the House.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/21/politics/republicans-nancy-pelosi-georgia/index.html|title=Trump and Republicans Don\u2019t Want Pelosi To Go|last=Bradner|first=Eric|date=June 22, 2017|publisher=CNN|access-date=October 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn the June 20 runoff, Ossoff was defeated by Handel, 51.78% to 48.22%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/70059/Web02-state/#/|title=Election Night Reporting|website=results.enr.clarityelections.com}}</ref> According to ''[[Atlanta Magazine]]'', \"while his percentage of the total vote remained steady from April to now, Ossoff garnered 32,220 more votes in those three months, a 34 percent increase ... Ossoff and his allies might have scooped up nearly every Democrat vote there was to get\u2014and it still wasn't enough to overcome the GOP's numerical advantage.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/planned-parenthoods-800000-fight-get-jon-ossoff-elected-wasnt-enough/ |title=Planned Parenthood's $800,000 fight to get Jon Ossoff elected wasn't enough|date=June 21, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that Ossoff \"produced probably the strongest Democratic turnout in an off-year election in at least a decade\", \"brought a surprising number of irregular young and nonwhite voters to the polls,\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/26/upshot/why-strong-turnout-was-not-enough-for-democrats-in-georgia.html|title=Democrats' Turnout in Georgia Blew Past Typical Off-Year Levels |first=Nate|last=Cohn|date=June 26, 2017|work=The New York Times}}</ref> and nearly doubled youth turnout in the Sixth District from the 2014 midterm election.<ref name=\"auto\"/> However, according to the ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'', \"surging Democratic turnout wasn't enough to overcome heavy GOP voting in a district where Republicans far outnumber Democrats.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/handel-preps-another-6th-district-campaign-ossoff-hints-comeback/PsDYoQhTSRIsq6myncmmuO/|title=Handel preps another 6th District campaign as Ossoff hints at comeback|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|last=Greg Bluestein|website=ajc}}</ref> Following reports of the election results, Frank Bruni in an op-ed for ''The New York Times'' characterized the race as \"demoralizing for Democrats\".<ref>Bruni, Frank. [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/20/opinion/georgia-election-karen-handel-jon-ossoff.html After Georgia Election, Democrats Are Demoralized, Again], ''The New York Times'', June 20, 2017.</ref> This was as close as a Democrat had come to winning this district since it assumed its current configuration as a northern suburban district in 1992; Democratic challengers had won more than 40 percent of the vote only twice before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/ContainerHistory.html?ContainerID=421|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 Container Detail Page|publisher=ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 23, 2018, Ossoff announced he would not seek the seat in the regular election in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2018#District 6|2018]]; the seat was won by Democrat [[Lucy McBath]] in Nov. 2018.<ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/ossoff-not-seeking-rematch-in-georgia-race-for-us-house-seat/2018/02/23/69ff3098-18d0-11e8-930c-45838ad0d77a_story.html ]{{dead link|date=April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===2020 Senate race===\n{{main|2020 United States Senate election in Georgia}}\nOssoff will run in the Georgia US Senate Democratic Primary election to try to unseat Republican Senator [[David Perdue]] in the [[2020 United States Senate election in Georgia|2020 Georgia Senate election]].<ref name=\"NYT 2020\"/> Three other Democrats are already running in the primary: former Mayor [[Teresa Tomlinson]] of Columbus; and [[Sarah Riggs Amico]], who ran for lieutenant governor last year on [[Stacey Abrams]]\u2019s ticket.<ref name=\"NYT 2020\"/> Ossoff was endorsed by [[John Lewis (civil rights leader)|John Lewis]].<ref name=\"NYT 2020\"/>\n\n===Political positions===\nAccording to ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Ossoff has \"[[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] positions on women's issues and health care\" and \"moderate stances on jobs and security.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Charles Bethea |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/can-this-democrat-win-the-georgia-sixth|title=Can This Democrat Win the Georgia Sixth?|date=March 3, 2017|website=The New Yorker}}</ref> According to [[Matthew Yglesias]] of ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', Ossoff has run an\" Obama-style campaign\", and has placed himself in the middle between grassroots progressive activists in the Democratic party and the more conservative and moderate Blue Dog Southern Democrats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/6/13/15786220/jon-ossoff-ad|title=That Jon Ossoff's message seems moderate is a sign of how far Democrats have shifted|work=Vox|access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> According to the ''New York Times'', Ossoff's campaign has distanced itself from the national Democratic Party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/us/politics/georgia-special-election-ossoff-handel.html|title=Takeaways From the Georgia Special Election Debate: A Sharper Clash|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=June 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 13, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> According to the ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'', the Ossoff campaign opted not to turn the special election into a referendum on Trump's alleged scandals, but to focus on \"policy decisions by the president and congressional Republicans.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Paul Kane|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/2017/05/20/4dbc06e6-3d7e-11e7-a058-ddbb23c75d82_story.html|title=Analysis: For Democrats, special elections may be preview of 2018 campaigns|website=The Washington Post|date=May 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOssoff has been sharply critical of President [[Donald Trump]], criticizing his \"divisive approach to government\"<ref>{{Cite news|author=Cristiano Lima|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/04/georgia-ossoff-special-election-237307|title=Georgia Democrat rebuffs Trump: 'I don't have great personal admiration' for him|work=Politico|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref> and saying: \"I have great respect for the office. I don't have great personal admiration for the man himself.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/329242-george-dem-on-trump-i-dont-have-great-personal-admiration-for|title=Georgia Dem Ossoff: 'I don't have great personal admiration' for Trump|last=Greenwood|first=Max|work=The Hill|date=April 18, 2017}}</ref> After Trump sent out a [[Twitter|tweet]] the day before the April 19 primary, calling Ossoff a \"super Liberal Democrat\" who wanted to \"protect criminals, allow illegal immigration and raise taxes,\" Ossoff dismissed Trump's claims and called him \"misinformed.\"<ref>{{Cite news|author=Alex Seitz-Wald|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/democrats-vs-trump/trump-rips-top-democrat-jon-ossoff-georgia-special-election-n747361|title=Trump takes to Twitter to blast leading Dem as 'super Liberal'|publisher=NBC News|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref> [[FactCheck.org]] found that Trump's claim was a distortion, and that there was no evidence that Ossoff had ever advocated for any broad-based tax hikes.<ref name=\":5\"/> Nevertheless, Ossoff said that he would be willing to work with Trump on issues of mutual interest, such as [[infrastructure]] spending.<ref name=\":3\" /> He said, \"If the administration introduces a fiscally responsible infrastructure bill, I'll work in a bipartisan way to make sure it delivers transformative solutions to Georgia.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|author=Greg Bluestein|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/04/17/how-top-sixth-district-contenders-stack-up-on-healthcare-taxes-and-transportation/|title=How top Sixth District contenders stack up on healthcare, taxes and transportation|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref> After [[Donald Trump's disclosure of classified information to Russia|Trump's disclosure of classified information to Russia]], Ossoff said of impeachment that \"I don't think we're there.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|author=Greg Bluestein|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/05/19/ossoff-on-trump-impeachment-i-dont-think-were-there/|title=Ossoff on Trump impeachment: 'I don't think we're there'|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 30, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff called for \"a full and transparent and independent assessment of what [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|level of interference there was by Russian intelligence services in the U.S. election]]. And overseers in Congress and any [[Special counsel|independent counsel]] or commission to do so should follow those facts wherever they lead.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nOssoff supports [[Abortion-rights movements|abortion rights]] and access to [[birth control|contraception]].<ref name=\":1\">{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/176134/jon-ossoff/#.WPh-4lOLSfQ|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|access-date=April 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nOssoff opposes prison sentencing for [[drug liberalization|nonviolent drug offenses]].<ref name=\":1\" /> His website says, \"Violent crime, murder, rape, human trafficking, and corruption are rampant, while we spend billions locking up nonviolent drug offenders.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/blogs/right-turn/wp/2017/04/17/the-georgia-special-election-shows-why-trump-may-sink-the-gop/|title=The Georgia special election shows why Trump may sink the GOP|last=Rubin|first=Jennifer|date=April 17, 2017|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nOssoff opposes tax increases, and has called for reduced taxes on small businesses and to simplify small business tax filing.<ref name=\":2\" /> He supports [[tax credit]]s for small businesses.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|authors=Robert Farley & Eugene Kiely|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2017/04/trump-distorts-ossoffs-record/|title=Trump Distorts Ossoff's Record|date=April 18, 2017|publisher=FactCheck.org}}</ref> He has called for the repeal of \"wasteful, anti-competitive special interest subsidies that make it hard for entrepreneurs to raise capital, enter the market, create jobs, and compete with larger firms who have lobbyists in Washington.\"<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":5\"/> He has cast himself as an opponent of unnecessary government spending, saying, for instance, that \"there's $16 billion in duplicate programs. That can be cut,\" an assertion that PolitiFact rated \"Mostly True\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2017/apr/27/jon-ossoff/checking-jon-ossoff-16-billion-government-waste/|title=Checking Jon Ossoff on $16 billion in government waste|work=@politifact|access-date=June 17, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe accepts the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate]], and has said that \"climate change is a threat to our security and prosperity\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/trump-looms-over-georgia-special-election-a-proxy-battle-for-2018/2017/06/10/a9fddce4-4ddd-11e7-9669-250d0b15f83b_story.html|title=Trump looms over Georgia special election, a proxy battle for 2018|last=https://www.facebook.com/pages/Karen-Tumulty/1410916925870676|website=The Washington Post|access-date=June 12, 2017}}</ref> He supports American participation in the [[Paris Agreement]], and has pledged to \"work to make the United States a global leader against [[climate change]].\"<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/us/politics/georgia-special-election-ossoff-handel.html|title=Takeaways From the Georgia Special Election Debate: A Sharper Clash|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=June 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 8, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHe supports the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare).<ref name=\":1\"/> His health care policy aims to serve three basic principles: \"One, no American should suffer or die from preventable or treatable illness. Two, no one should go broke because they get sick. And three, no business should go under or lay off employees because it can't keep up with health insurance premiums.\"<ref name=\":4\"/> He does not support pushing for a single-payer health care system.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOssoff opposed both the March 2017 and May 2017 versions of the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]], the House Republican bill that repeals and replaces the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Elise Viebeck & David Weigel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/gop-candidate-now-embracing-trump-in-georgias-6th-district-runoff/2017/04/30/28a89bb0-2c5f-11e7-b605-33413c691853_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=April 30, 2017|title=GOP candidate now embracing Trump in Georgia's 6th District runoff}}</ref> Ossoff said that the May 2017 version was worse than the earlier one \"because it does even less to protect those with [[preexisting condition]]s. And those are children and families here in Georgia who need to be able to get affordable health insurance despite a pre-existing condition.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Greg Bluestein|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/05/04/a-6th-district-rift-over-the-house-healthcare-plan-in-tom-prices-old-turf/|title=A 6th District rift over the House healthcare plan in Tom Price's old turf|date=May 4, 2016|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref>\n\nOssoff supports comprehensive [[immigration reform]] that would both strengthen enforcement along the [[United States-Mexico border|Mexican border]] and provide a path to citizenship for some [[Illegal immigration to the United States|undocumented immigrants]].<ref name=\":5\"/> This position is generally consistent with the stance of most congressional Democrats and a number of prominent Republicans, including President [[George W. Bush]].<ref name=\":5\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nOssoff's mother Heather Fenton, an Australian immigrant,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/can-this-democrat-win-the-georgia-sixth|title=Can This Democrat Win the Georgia Sixth?|last=Bethea|first=Charles|date=March 3, 2017|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=March 8, 2017}}</ref> co-founded NewPower PAC, an organization that works to elect women to local office across Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.myajc.com/2017/01/05/another-democrat-announces-for-tom-prices-seat-with-some-hefty-advantages|title=Another Democrat Announces for Tom Price's Seat with some Hefty Advantages|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|date=January 5, 2016|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"fenton-ga\">{{cite web|url=https://newpowerpacga.org/about-us/our-team|title=About New Power PAC}}</ref> His father, who is of [[History of the Jews in Russia|Russian Jewish]] and [[Lithuanian Jews|Lithuanian Jewish]] descent, owns a specialist publishing company.<ref name=\":0\"/> Ossoff was raised Jewish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2017/03/21/news-opinion/politics/a-jewish-candidate-gives-democrats-hope-in-atlantas-suburbs|title=A Jewish candidate gives Democrats hope in Atlanta's suburbs|last=Kampeas|first=Ron|date=March 21, 2017|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]|access-date=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2017, Ossoff's campaign confirmed that he and his longtime girlfriend Alisha Kramer, an [[Emory University]] medical student, are engaged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox5atlanta.com/news/253144045-story|title=Jon Ossoff engaged to long-time girlfriend amid 6th District Race|publisher=[[WAGA-TV]]|date=May 7, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2017/05/08/dem-candidate-for-georgia-house-seat-jon-ossoff-engaged/|title=Democratic candidate for Georgia House seat Jon Ossoff engaged|last=Polus|first=Sarah|date=May 8, 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=May 11, 2017|last2=Polus|first2=Sarah|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[New Day (TV series)|New Day]]'' || Self || Episode: \"5.173\"\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Deadline: White House]]'' || Self || Episode: \"1.26\"\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Stacey on the Frontline'' || Executive producer || Episode: \"Girls, Guns and ISIS\"\n|-\n| 2015 || ''Justice!'' || Executive producer || TV movie documentary\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015 || ''Africa Investigates'' || Executive producer || 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015 || ''People and Power'' || Executive producer || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014 || ''Living with Ebola'' || Executive producer & writer || TV movie documentary\n|-\n| 2014 || ''The Battle for Africa'' || Executive producer & writer || TV miniseries documentary\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* [https://electjon.com Jon Ossoff for Congress website]\n* {{IMDb name|7344702|Jonathan Ossoff}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ossoff, Jon}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:American documentary film producers]]\n[[Category:American people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Atlanta]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Democratic nominee for Congress in the 2017 special election}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox politician\n|name = Jon Ossoff\n|image = Ossoff-Mar-15-17.png\n|birth_name = Thomas Jonathan Ossoff\n|birth_date = {{birth date and age|1987|2|16}}\n|birth_place = [[Atlanta]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]], U.S.\n|death_date = \n|death_place = \n|party = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|education = [[Georgetown University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[London School of Economics]]<br>([[Master of Science|MS]])\n|website = {{url|electjon.com|Campaign website}}\n}}\n'''Thomas Jonathan Ossoff''' (born February 16, 1987)<ref name=\":6\">Mr. Thomas Jonathan Ossoff, Insight Twi Limited; [http://directors.findthecompany.co.uk/l/8809030/Mr-Thomas-Jonathan-Ossoff findthecompany.co.uk] (subscription required)</ref> is an American media executive, investigative journalist <ref name=\"AJC 2020\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.ajc.com/blog/politics/georgia-senate-ossoff-nets-another-ends-quarter-with-hand/xR53pjf70RyulxACa30UEL/ |title=Georgia Senate: Ossoff nets another $1M, ends quarter with $1.8M on hand |last=Bluestein |first=Greg |date=2020-04-15 |work=The Atlanta-Journal Constitution |access-date=2020-04-17 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>, and activist.\n\nSince 2013, Ossoff has served as managing director and CEO of Insight TWI, a multi-Emmy award winning investigative television production company that produces investigations for news channels around the world. <ref name=\"Variety\">{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2020/politics/news/jon-ossoff-senate-georgia-1203522791/ |title=Doc Producer Jon Ossoff on His Run for a U.S. Senate Seat in Georgia |last=Ravindran |first=Manori |date=2020-03-05 |work=Variety |access-date=2020-04-17 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n \nOssoff was the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] nominee for Congress in the historically expensive [[Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017|2017 special election]] in [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]]; he lost with 48.2% of the vote to Republican [[Karen Handel]]'s 51.8%.<ref name=\"insights-twi\">{{cite web|url=https://insighttwi.com/contact|title=Insight TWI: The World Investigates}}</ref><ref name=\"Hefty-Advantages-AJC\">{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/01/05/another-democrat-announces-for-tom-prices-seat-with-some-hefty-advantages|title=A Democrat with a pile of cash commitments announces for Tom Price's seat|work=[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=February 20, 2017|last=Bluestein|first=Greg}}</ref><ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web|title=About Jon|url=https://electjon.com/about-jon/|publisher=Jon Ossoff for Congress|year=2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Barrow\">{{cite web|author=Bill Barrow|url=https://elections.ap.org/content/georgia-special-election-shapes-referendum-trump|title=Georgia special election shapes up as referendum on Trump|date=February 14, 2017|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n\nOssoff is running in the Democratic primary for the [[2020 United States Senate election in Georgia |2020 Georgia Senate election]] against Republican incumbent Senator [[David Perdue]].<ref name=\"NYT 2020\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/09/us/politics/jon-ossoff-2020-georgia-senate.html |title=Jon Ossoff Will Run for Senate in Georgia |last=Astor |first=Maggie |date=2019-09-09 |work=The New York Times |access-date=2019-09-10 |language=en-US |issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nOssoff was born on February 16, 1987,<ref name=\":6\" /> in [[Atlanta]], Georgia. He was raised in [[Northlake, Georgia|Northlake]], an [[Unincorporated area|unincorporated community]] in [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]].<ref name=\"electjon.com\">{{cite web|url=https://electjon.com/news/2017/1/4/jon-ossoff-announces-congressional-bid-in-georgia|title=Jon Ossoff Announces Congressional Bid|date=January 5, 2017|accessdate=February 21, 2017|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170222084607/https://electjon.com/news/2017/1/4/jon-ossoff-announces-congressional-bid-in-georgia|archivedate=February 22, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff attended the [[The Paideia School|Paideia School]], a small private school in Atlanta.<ref name=\":0\" /> While in high school, he interned for Georgia congressman and civil rights leader [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2009, Ossoff graduated from [[Georgetown University]]'s [[School of Foreign Service]] with a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree. He attended classes taught by former [[List of Secretaries of State of the United States|secretary of state]] [[Madeleine Albright]] and former [[List of Israeli ambassadors to the United States|Israeli ambassador to the United States]] [[Michael Oren]].<ref name=\"wp-2017-02-23\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/paloma/daily-202/2017/02/23/daily-202-will-anti-trump-backlash-let-democrats-win-the-georgia-special-election-to-replace-tom-price/58ae458be9b69b1406c75ceb/|title=The Daily 202: Will anti-Trump backlash let Democrats win the Georgia special election to replace Tom Price?|last=Hohmann|first=James|date=February 23, 2017|work=The Washington Post}}</ref><ref name=\"db-2017-03-01\">{{cite news|url=http://www.thedailybeast.com/articles/2017/02/27/could-the-resistance-start-with-georgia-s-special-election.html|title=Could The Resistance Start With Georgia's Special Election?|last=Murphy|first=Patricia|date=February 27, 2017|work=Daily Beast|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff went on to earn his [[Master of Science]] degree from [[London School of Economics]] in 2013.<ref name=\"wp-2017-02-23\" /><ref name=\"db-2017-03-01\" />\n\n== Political career ==\nOssoff worked as a national security staffer and aide to Rep. [[Hank Johnson]] for five years during which he drafted and managed legislative initiatives that passed the House and [[United States Senate|Senate]].<ref name=\"electjon.com\"/><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2017/apr/03/jon-ossoff/jon-ossoff-national-security-background/|title=How extensive was Jon Ossoff's national security background?|work=@politifact|access-date=April 6, 2017|language=en}}</ref> He had [[Security clearance#Top Secret|top-secret clearance]] for five months.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/326800-democrats-go-for-broke-in-race-for-tom-prices-seat|title=Democrats go for broke in race for Tom Price's seat|last=Weaver|first=Dustin|date=April 1, 2017|work=TheHill|access-date=April 6, 2017}}</ref> Since 2013, he has been managing partner and [[CEO]] of Insight TWI, a small business based in the United Kingdom<ref>https://insighttwi.com/contact.html</ref> which produces investigations targeting corrupt officials and [[organized crime]] for international news organizations.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/no-blood-diamonds-or-gunrunning-in-sight-why-the-documentary-film-sierra-leone-an-artist-s-journey-a7311421.html|title=No Blood Diamonds or Gunrunning in Sight, Why the Documentary Film?|work=Independent|date=September 16, 2016|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref> In 2016, Ossoff was an executive producer for a documentary film by Insight TWI for [[BBC Three]]; the film exposed atrocities committed by [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|ISIL in Iraq]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://insighttwi.com/films/girlsgunsisis|accessdate=February 23, 2017|title=Girls, Guns and Isis|publisher=Insight TWI, Ltd.}}</ref>\n\n===2017 special election===\n{{main|Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017}}\n\nAfter learning that [[Tom Price (American politician)|Tom Price]] of Georgia's 6th district had been appointed secretary of Health and Human Services, Ossoff announced his candidacy for this [[Georgia's 6th congressional district special election, 2017|special election]] on January 5, 2017.<ref name=\"db-2017-03-01\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/01/05/another-democrat-announces-for-tom-prices-seat-with-some-hefty-advantages/|title=A Democrat with a pile of cash commitments announces for Tom Price's seat|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=January 5, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff quickly emerged as the most viable Democratic candidate out of a large field of candidates.<ref>{{cite web|author=Ed Kilgore|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/02/georgia-special-house-election-still-gops-race-to-lose.html|title=Georgia's Special Election to Replace Tom Price Is Still the GOP's Race to Lose|date=February 16, 2017|magazine=New York}}</ref> He was endorsed by prominent figures such as Congressmen [[Hank Johnson]] and [[John Lewis (Georgia politician)|John Lewis]],<ref name=\"Barrow\"/><ref name=\"mh-2017-02-23\">{{cite news|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/news/politics-government/article134490239.html|title=Democrats hope Trump backlash begins in this ruby-red House seat|last=Roarty|first=Alex|date=February 23, 2017|work=The Miami Herald|accessdate=February 25, 2017}}</ref> and [[Georgia House of Representatives|state House]] Democratic Leader [[Stacey Abrams]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/02/09/democrat-aiming-for-tom-prices-seat-picks-up-key-supporter/|title=Democrat aiming for Tom Price's seat picks up key supporter|date=February 9, 2017|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref><ref name=\"wx-2017-03-01\">{{cite news |url=http://www.11alive.com/news/politics/elections/race-to-replace-price-leading-in-polls-ossoff-doesnt-live-in-district/414685623|title=Race to replace Price: Leading in polls, Ossoff doesn't live in district|last=Darnell|first=Tim|publisher=WXIA|date=February 28, 2017}}</ref> He also received public support from Vermont Senator and 2016 Democratic presidential candidate [[Bernie Sanders]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/campaign/329927-sanders-endorses-ossoff-but-wont-call-him-a-progressive|title=Sanders endorses Ossoff, but won't call him a progressive|first=Will|last=Sommer|date=April 21, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/democrats-reload-for-georgia-runoff-but-party-divisions-remain-1492626238|title=Democrats Reload for Georgia Runoff, But Party Divisions Remain|first1=Reid J.|last1=Epstein|first2=Natalie|last2=Andrews|date=April 19, 2017|publisher=|accessdate=October 24, 2018|via=www.wsj.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/democrats-vs-trump/bernie-sanders-clarifies-support-jon-ossoff-after-dustup-n749491|title=Sanders clarifies support for Ossoff after dustup|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=October 24, 2018}}</ref> Ossoff raised over $8.3 million by early April of that year.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.myajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/ossoff-pulls-record-donations-for-georgia-special-election/MqGzLMjrzVRR8jE5YGs3rL/|title=Democrat Ossoff rakes in huge amount in 6th District race|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|access-date=April 6, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the ''[[Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'', Ossoff \"transformed what was expected to be a quiet battle for a long-safe Republican seat into a proxy fight over Trump, the health care overhaul and the partisan struggle for suburbia.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/handel-preps-another-6th-district-campaign-ossoff-hints-comeback/PsDYoQhTSRIsq6myncmmuO/|title=Handel preps another 6th District campaign as Ossoff hints at comeback|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref> When Ossoff entered the race, the [[Cook Partisan Voting Index]] rated [[Georgia's 6th congressional district]] at R+14;<ref>https://web.archive.org/web/20170617193745/http://cookpolitical.com/file/2013-04-49.pdf</ref> the district was not considered competitive, and had been represented in Congress by Republicans since 1978.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://heavy.com/news/2017/04/georgia-sixth-congressional-district-last-most-recent-democrat-jon-ossoff/|title=When Was the Last Time a Democrat Represented Georgia\u2019s Sixth Congressional District?}}</ref> Less than two months before Ossoff\u2019s announcement, Republican Congressman Tom Price had been re-elected in a landslide with 62% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/georgia-house-district-6-price-stooksbury|title=Georgia U.S. House 6th District Results: Tom Price Wins}}</ref>\n\nOssoff grew up in the 6th district, where his family still resides, although as of the election he lived about {{convert|1.5|mi|km}} outside the district's boundaries. As a result, he was unable to vote for himself in the primary. He has said that he temporarily lives in the neighboring 4th District so that his fianc\u00e9e, an [[Emory University School of Medicine|Emory University medical student]], can walk to the hospital where she works. Ossoff says he intends to move back to the 6th district after his fianc\u00e9e completes her medical studies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/18/politics/georgia-candidate-shrugs-off-district-issues-cnntv/index.html|title=Dem hopeful dismisses questions about residency|authors=Josiah Ryan|publisher=CNN|accessdate=April 18, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"db-2017-03-01\" /><ref>Robert Costa, [https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/georgia-house-race-stokes-gop-identity-crisis--and-opportunity-for-democrats/2017/04/18/a2231a48-242f-11e7-b503-9d616bd5a305_story.html \"Republicans avoid big loss by forcing runoff in Ga. House race\"], ''The Washington Post'', April 18, 2017.</ref>\n\nOn April 18, 2017, no candidate received 50% of the vote in the [[nonpartisan blanket primary|blanket primary]] (\"jungle primary\").<ref name=CNNShort>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/04/18/politics/georgia-house-6th-special-election-jon-ossoff/index.html|title=Ossoff falls just short in Georgia special election|first=Eric |last=Bradner|publisher=CNN|access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff led with about 48.1% of the vote, Republican candidate [[Karen Handel]] received 19.8%, while the remainder of votes were scattered for 16 other candidates.<ref name=\"GASOS04192017\">{{cite news |date=April 19, 2017 |title=Unofficial Results |url=http://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/67317/Web02-state/#/ |publisher=Georgia Secretary of State |location=Atlanta, Georgia |access-date=April 19, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"NYTApril\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/elections/results/georgia-house-special-election-district-6|title=Election Results: Ossoff, Handel Advance in Race for Georgia's Sixth Congressional District |work=The New York Times|date=April 19, 2017}}</ref> Because no candidate secured an absolute majority, the top two vote-getters, Ossoff and Handel, competed in a [[runoff election]] on June 20, 2017.<ref name=\":1\"/><ref name=\"NYTApril\"/> Ossoff won all but 1% of the Democratic vote, while the Republican vote was more heavily split. Republicans collectively won 51.2% of the overall vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2017/04/ossoff-to-face-handel-in-georgia-special-election-runoff.html|title=Ossoff Falls Short of a Majority in Georgia House Race, Heads to Runoff|first=Ed|last=Kilgore|work=New York|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOssoff broke national fundraising records for a [[U.S. House]] candidate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/09/us/politics/ossoff-handel-georgia-house-special-election.html?mcubz=0|title=Ossoff Raises $23 Million in Most Expensive House Race in History|website=The New York Times|access-date=2017-07-13}}</ref> In total, Ossoff's campaign raised more than $23 million, two-thirds of which was contributed by small-dollar donors nationwide.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wired.com/story/ossoff-social-media-campaign/|title=JON OSSOFF, THE CONGRESSIONAL CANDIDATE SOCIAL MEDIA BUILT|website=Wired|access-date=2017-07-13}}</ref> Ossoff's opponent, Handel, and national Republican groups attacked Ossoff for raising significant small-dollar contributions from outside of Georgia, although Handel's campaign received the bulk of its support from super PACs and other outside groups, including those funded anonymously by so-called \"[[dark money]]\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.politifact.com/truth-o-meter/article/2017/jun/08/ga-6-race-fact-checking-attacks-campaign-cash/|title=In GA-6 race, fact-checking attacks about campaign cash|website=Politifact|access-date=2017-07-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/6/19/15827686/georgia-election-ossoff-money|title=Guess who's funding multimillion-dollar ad blitzes slamming Ossoff's out-of-state donors?|website=Vox|access-date=2017-07-13}}</ref> Combined spending by the campaigns and outside groups on their behalf added up to over $55 million, which was the most expensive House Congressional election in U.S. history.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2017/06/20/us/politics/georgia-6th-most-expensive-house-election.html|title=Who Financed the Georgia Sixth, the Most Expensive House Election Ever|last=Parlapiano|first=Alicia|date=2017-06-20|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-06-23|last2=Shorey|first2=Rachel|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During the campaign, Republican strategy focused on connecting Ossoff to House Democratic Leader [[Nancy Pelosi]], a polarizing and unpopular figure amongst Republicans; Ossoff declined to say whether he would, if elected, support Pelosi for Speaker of the House.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/06/21/politics/republicans-nancy-pelosi-georgia/index.html|title=Trump and Republicans Don\u2019t Want Pelosi To Go|last=Bradner|first=Eric|date=June 22, 2017|publisher=CNN|access-date=October 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn the June 20 runoff, Ossoff was defeated by Handel, 51.78% to 48.22%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://results.enr.clarityelections.com/GA/70059/Web02-state/#/|title=Election Night Reporting|website=results.enr.clarityelections.com}}</ref> According to ''[[Atlanta Magazine]]'', \"while his percentage of the total vote remained steady from April to now, Ossoff garnered 32,220 more votes in those three months, a 34 percent increase ... Ossoff and his allies might have scooped up nearly every Democrat vote there was to get\u2014and it still wasn't enough to overcome the GOP's numerical advantage.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.atlantamagazine.com/news-culture-articles/planned-parenthoods-800000-fight-get-jon-ossoff-elected-wasnt-enough/ |title=Planned Parenthood's $800,000 fight to get Jon Ossoff elected wasn't enough|date=June 21, 2017}}</ref> ''[[The New York Times]]'' reported that Ossoff \"produced probably the strongest Democratic turnout in an off-year election in at least a decade\", \"brought a surprising number of irregular young and nonwhite voters to the polls,\"<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/26/upshot/why-strong-turnout-was-not-enough-for-democrats-in-georgia.html|title=Democrats' Turnout in Georgia Blew Past Typical Off-Year Levels |first=Nate|last=Cohn|date=June 26, 2017|work=The New York Times}}</ref> and nearly doubled youth turnout in the Sixth District from the 2014 midterm election.<ref name=\"auto\"/> However, according to the ''Atlanta Journal-Constitution'', \"surging Democratic turnout wasn't enough to overcome heavy GOP voting in a district where Republicans far outnumber Democrats.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ajc.com/news/state--regional-govt--politics/handel-preps-another-6th-district-campaign-ossoff-hints-comeback/PsDYoQhTSRIsq6myncmmuO/|title=Handel preps another 6th District campaign as Ossoff hints at comeback|first=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|last=Greg Bluestein|website=ajc}}</ref> Following reports of the election results, Frank Bruni in an op-ed for ''The New York Times'' characterized the race as \"demoralizing for Democrats\".<ref>Bruni, Frank. [https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/20/opinion/georgia-election-karen-handel-jon-ossoff.html After Georgia Election, Democrats Are Demoralized, Again], ''The New York Times'', June 20, 2017.</ref> This was as close as a Democrat had come to winning this district since it assumed its current configuration as a northern suburban district in 1992; Democratic challengers had won more than 40 percent of the vote only twice before.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/ContainerHistory.html?ContainerID=421|title=Our Campaigns \u2013 Container Detail Page|publisher=ourcampaigns.com|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn February 23, 2018, Ossoff announced he would not seek the seat in the regular election in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Georgia, 2018#District 6|2018]]; the seat was won by Democrat [[Lucy McBath]] in Nov., 2018.<ref>https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/ossoff-not-seeking-rematch-in-georgia-race-for-us-house-seat/2018/02/23/69ff3098-18d0-11e8-930c-45838ad0d77a_story.html</ref>\n\n===2020 Senate race===\n{{main|2020 United States Senate election in Georgia}}\nOssoff will run in the Georgia US Senate Democratic Primary election to try to unseat Republican Senator [[David Perdue]] in the [[2020 United States Senate election in Georgia|2020 Georgia Senate election]].<ref name=\"NYT 2020\"/> Three other Democrats are already running in the primary: former Mayor [[Teresa Tomlinson]] of Columbus; and [[Sarah Riggs Amico]], who ran for lieutenant governor last year on [[Stacey Abrams]]\u2019s ticket.<ref name=\"NYT 2020\"/> Ossoff was endorsed by [[John Lewis (civil rights leader)|John Lewis]].<ref name=\"NYT 2020\"/>\n\n===Political positions===\nAccording to ''[[The New Yorker]]'', Ossoff has \"[[Progressivism in the United States|progressive]] positions on women's issues and health care\" and \"moderate stances on jobs and security.\"<ref>{{Cite web|author=Charles Bethea |url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/can-this-democrat-win-the-georgia-sixth|title=Can This Democrat Win the Georgia Sixth?|date=March 3, 2017|website=The New Yorker}}</ref> According to [[Matthew Yglesias]] of ''[[Vox (website)|Vox]]'', Ossoff has run an\" Obama-style campaign\", and has placed himself in the middle between grassroots progressive activists in the Democratic party and the more conservative and moderate Blue Dog Southern Democrats.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vox.com/policy-and-politics/2017/6/13/15786220/jon-ossoff-ad|title=That Jon Ossoff's message seems moderate is a sign of how far Democrats have shifted|work=Vox|access-date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> According to the ''New York Times'', Ossoff's campaign has distanced itself from the national Democratic Party.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/us/politics/georgia-special-election-ossoff-handel.html|title=Takeaways From the Georgia Special Election Debate: A Sharper Clash|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=June 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 13, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> According to the ''[[The Washington Post|Washington Post]]'', the Ossoff campaign opted not to turn the special election into a referendum on Trump's alleged scandals, but to focus on \"policy decisions by the president and congressional Republicans.\"<ref>{{Cite web|author=Paul Kane|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/2017/05/20/4dbc06e6-3d7e-11e7-a058-ddbb23c75d82_story.html|title=Analysis: For Democrats, special elections may be preview of 2018 campaigns|website=The Washington Post|date=May 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOssoff has been sharply critical of President [[Donald Trump]], criticizing his \"divisive approach to government\"<ref>{{Cite news|author=Cristiano Lima|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2017/04/georgia-ossoff-special-election-237307|title=Georgia Democrat rebuffs Trump: 'I don't have great personal admiration' for him|work=Politico|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref> and saying: \"I have great respect for the office. I don't have great personal admiration for the man himself.\"<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/329242-george-dem-on-trump-i-dont-have-great-personal-admiration-for|title=Georgia Dem Ossoff: 'I don't have great personal admiration' for Trump|last=Greenwood|first=Max|work=The Hill|date=April 18, 2017}}</ref> After Trump sent out a [[Twitter|tweet]] the day before the April 19 primary, calling Ossoff a \"super Liberal Democrat\" who wanted to \"protect criminals, allow illegal immigration and raise taxes,\" Ossoff dismissed Trump's claims and called him \"misinformed.\"<ref>{{Cite news|author=Alex Seitz-Wald|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/storyline/democrats-vs-trump/trump-rips-top-democrat-jon-ossoff-georgia-special-election-n747361|title=Trump takes to Twitter to blast leading Dem as 'super Liberal'|publisher=NBC News|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref> [[FactCheck.org]] found that Trump's claim was a distortion, and that there was no evidence that Ossoff had ever advocated for any broad-based tax hikes.<ref name=\":5\"/> Nevertheless, Ossoff said that he would be willing to work with Trump on issues of mutual interest, such as [[infrastructure]] spending.<ref name=\":3\" /> He said, \"If the administration introduces a fiscally responsible infrastructure bill, I'll work in a bipartisan way to make sure it delivers transformative solutions to Georgia.\"<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|author=Greg Bluestein|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/04/17/how-top-sixth-district-contenders-stack-up-on-healthcare-taxes-and-transportation/|title=How top Sixth District contenders stack up on healthcare, taxes and transportation|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=April 17, 2017}}</ref> After [[Donald Trump's disclosure of classified information to Russia|Trump's disclosure of classified information to Russia]], Ossoff said of impeachment that \"I don't think we're there.\"<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|author=Greg Bluestein|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/05/19/ossoff-on-trump-impeachment-i-dont-think-were-there/|title=Ossoff on Trump impeachment: 'I don't think we're there'|work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=May 30, 2017}}</ref> Ossoff called for \"a full and transparent and independent assessment of what [[Russian interference in the 2016 United States elections|level of interference there was by Russian intelligence services in the U.S. election]]. And overseers in Congress and any [[Special counsel|independent counsel]] or commission to do so should follow those facts wherever they lead.\"<ref name=\":7\" />\n\nOssoff supports [[Abortion-rights movements|abortion rights]] and access to [[birth control|contraception]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/176134/jon-ossoff/#.WPh-4lOLSfQ|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|website=Vote Smart|access-date=April 20, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nOssoff opposes prison sentencing for [[drug liberalization|nonviolent drug offenses]].<ref name=\":1\" /> His website says, \"Violent crime, murder, rape, human trafficking, and corruption are rampant, while we spend billions locking up nonviolent drug offenders.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/pb/blogs/right-turn/wp/2017/04/17/the-georgia-special-election-shows-why-trump-may-sink-the-gop/|title=The Georgia special election shows why Trump may sink the GOP|last=Rubin|first=Jennifer|date=April 17, 2017|work=The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\nOssoff opposes tax increases, and has called for reduced taxes on small businesses and to simplify small business tax filing.<ref name=\":2\" /> He supports [[tax credit]]s for small businesses.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|authors=Robert Farley & Eugene Kiely|url=http://www.factcheck.org/2017/04/trump-distorts-ossoffs-record/|title=Trump Distorts Ossoff's Record|date=April 18, 2017|publisher=FactCheck.org}}</ref> He has called for the repeal of \"wasteful, anti-competitive special interest subsidies that make it hard for entrepreneurs to raise capital, enter the market, create jobs, and compete with larger firms who have lobbyists in Washington.\"<ref name=\":2\"/><ref name=\":5\"/> He has cast himself as an opponent of unnecessary government spending, saying, for instance, that \"there's $16 billion in duplicate programs. That can be cut,\" an assertion that PolitiFact rated \"Mostly True\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.politifact.com/georgia/statements/2017/apr/27/jon-ossoff/checking-jon-ossoff-16-billion-government-waste/|title=Checking Jon Ossoff on $16 billion in government waste|work=@politifact|access-date=June 17, 2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nHe accepts the [[Scientific opinion on climate change|scientific consensus on climate]], and has said that \"climate change is a threat to our security and prosperity\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/trump-looms-over-georgia-special-election-a-proxy-battle-for-2018/2017/06/10/a9fddce4-4ddd-11e7-9669-250d0b15f83b_story.html|title=Trump looms over Georgia special election, a proxy battle for 2018|last=https://www.facebook.com/pages/Karen-Tumulty/1410916925870676|website=The Washington Post|access-date=June 12, 2017}}</ref> He supports American participation in the [[Paris Agreement]], and has pledged to \"work to make the United States a global leader against [[climate change]].\"<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/06/08/us/politics/georgia-special-election-ossoff-handel.html|title=Takeaways From the Georgia Special Election Debate: A Sharper Clash|last=Burns|first=Alexander|date=June 8, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=June 8, 2017|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nHe supports the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act|Affordable Care Act]] (Obamacare).<ref name=\":1\"/> His health care policy aims to serve three basic principles: \"One, no American should suffer or die from preventable or treatable illness. Two, no one should go broke because they get sick. And three, no business should go under or lay off employees because it can't keep up with health insurance premiums.\"<ref name=\":4\"/> He does not support pushing for a single-payer health care system.<ref name=\":8\" />\n\nOssoff opposed both the March 2017 and May 2017 versions of the [[American Health Care Act of 2017|American Health Care Act]], the House Republican bill that repeals and replaces the Affordable Care Act.<ref>{{Cite news|author=Elise Viebeck & David Weigel|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/powerpost/gop-candidate-now-embracing-trump-in-georgias-6th-district-runoff/2017/04/30/28a89bb0-2c5f-11e7-b605-33413c691853_story.html|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=April 30, 2017|title=GOP candidate now embracing Trump in Georgia's 6th District runoff}}</ref> Ossoff said that the May 2017 version was worse than the earlier one \"because it does even less to protect those with [[preexisting condition]]s. And those are children and families here in Georgia who need to be able to get affordable health insurance despite a pre-existing condition.\"<ref>{{Cite web|author=Greg Bluestein|url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2017/05/04/a-6th-district-rift-over-the-house-healthcare-plan-in-tom-prices-old-turf/|title=A 6th District rift over the House healthcare plan in Tom Price's old turf|date=May 4, 2016|newspaper=Atlanta Journal-Constitution}}</ref>\n\nOssoff supports comprehensive [[immigration reform]] that would both strengthen enforcement along the [[United States-Mexico border|Mexican border]] and provide a path to citizenship for some [[Illegal immigration to the United States|undocumented immigrants]].<ref name=\":5\"/> This position is generally consistent with the stance of most congressional Democrats and a number of prominent Republicans, including President [[George W. Bush]].<ref name=\":5\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nOssoff's mother Heather Fenton, an Australian immigrant,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/can-this-democrat-win-the-georgia-sixth|title=Can This Democrat Win the Georgia Sixth?|last=Bethea|first=Charles|date=March 3, 2017|work=[[The New Yorker]]|access-date=March 8, 2017}}</ref> co-founded NewPower PAC, an organization that works to elect women to local office across Georgia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.blog.myajc.com/2017/01/05/another-democrat-announces-for-tom-prices-seat-with-some-hefty-advantages|title=Another Democrat Announces for Tom Price's Seat with some Hefty Advantages|work=Atlanta Journal Constitution|date=January 5, 2016|accessdate=February 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"fenton-ga\">{{cite web|url=https://newpowerpacga.org/about-us/our-team|title=About New Power PAC}}</ref> His father, who is of [[History of the Jews in Russia|Russian Jewish]] and [[Lithuanian Jews|Lithuanian Jewish]] descent, owns a specialist publishing company.<ref name=\":0\"/> Ossoff was raised Jewish.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/2017/03/21/news-opinion/politics/a-jewish-candidate-gives-democrats-hope-in-atlantas-suburbs|title=A Jewish candidate gives Democrats hope in Atlanta's suburbs|last=Kampeas|first=Ron|date=March 21, 2017|publisher=[[Jewish Telegraphic Agency]]|access-date=March 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn May 7, 2017, Ossoff's campaign confirmed that he and his longtime girlfriend Alisha Kramer, an [[Emory University]] medical student, are engaged.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fox5atlanta.com/news/253144045-story|title=Jon Ossoff engaged to long-time girlfriend amid 6th District Race|publisher=[[WAGA-TV]]|date=May 7, 2017|accessdate=May 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/reliable-source/wp/2017/05/08/dem-candidate-for-georgia-house-seat-jon-ossoff-engaged/|title=Democratic candidate for Georgia House seat Jon Ossoff engaged|last=Polus|first=Sarah|date=May 8, 2017|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=May 11, 2017|last2=Polus|first2=Sarah|issn=0190-8286}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[New Day (TV series)|New Day]]'' || Self || Episode: \"5.173\"\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Deadline: White House]]'' || Self || Episode: \"1.26\"\n|-\n| 2016 || ''Stacey on the Frontline'' || Executive producer || Episode: \"Girls, Guns and ISIS\"\n|-\n| 2015 || ''Justice!'' || Executive producer || TV movie documentary\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015 || ''Africa Investigates'' || Executive producer || 9 episodes\n|-\n| 2014\u20132015 || ''People and Power'' || Executive producer || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2014 || ''Living with Ebola'' || Executive producer & writer || TV movie documentary\n|-\n| 2014 || ''The Battle for Africa'' || Executive producer & writer || TV miniseries documentary\n\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat}}\n* [https://electjon.com Jon Ossoff for Congress website]\n* {{IMDb name|7344702|Jonathan Ossoff}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ossoff, Jon}}\n[[Category:1987 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London School of Economics]]\n[[Category:American documentary film producers]]\n[[Category:American people of Australian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Lithuanian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Russian-Jewish descent]]\n[[Category:Georgia (U.S. state) Democrats]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Atlanta]]\n", "name_user": "Muboshgu", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filling in 3 references usingReflinks, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jon_Ossoff"}
{"title_page": "Sarah Rose Nordgren", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sarah Rose Nordgren\n| occupation         = Poet\n| education          = [[Sarah Lawrence College]]<br>[[University of North Carolina at Greensboro]]<br>[[University of Cincinnati]]\n| awards             = [[Agnes Lynch Starrett Poetry Prize]]<br>James Wright Poetry Prize\n| website            =  {{URL|sarahrosenordgren.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Sarah Rose Nordgren''' is an American poet. She is the author of ''Darwin\u2019s Mother'', and of ''Best Bones'', winner of the [[Agnes Lynch Starrett Poetry Prize|Agnes Lynch Starrett Prize]] in 2013. \n\n==Early life and education==\nSarah Rose Nordgren was raised in [[Durham, North Carolina]]. She has a BA in Liberal Arts from [[Sarah Lawrence College]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sarahlawrence.edu/alumni/news/2016-08-26-sarah-rose-nordgren-04.html|title=Sarah Rose Nordgren \u201904|website=www.sarahlawrence.edu}}</ref>, an MFA in Poetry from The [[University of North Carolina at Greensboro]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfagreensboro.org/alumni/sarah-rose-nordgren/|title=Sarah Rose Nordgren - UNCG &#124; Creative WritingUNCG &#124; Creative Writing|first1=A. Call To|last1=Writers|first2=A. Call To|last2=Alumni}}</ref> where she held the [[Fred Chappell]] Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theparisamerican.com/poetry173.html|title=The Cell by Sarah Rose Nordgren|website=www.theparisamerican.com}}</ref>, and a PhD in English and Creative Writing from the [[University of Cincinnati]], with a Graduate Certificate in Women\u2019s, Gender, and Sexuality Studies<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://sarahrosenordgren.com/sarah-rose-nordgren-bio/|title=Sarah Rose Nordgren Bio &#124; Sara Rose Nordgren}}</ref>, where she was also a Taft Summer Research Fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://multisite.uc.edu/taft/fellowship/graduate-summer-fellows|title=Graduate Summer Fellows|website=multisite.uc.edu}}</ref> and a Ricking Dissertation Fellow.\n\n==Career==\nNordgren\u2019s first poetry collection, ''Best Bones'', was published in 2014 by [[University of Pittsburgh Press]]. The collection, with themes of myth, identity, domestic life, and loss, won the prestigious 2013 [[Agnes Lynch Starrett Poetry Prize|Agnes Lynch Starrett Prize]] for a first book.<ref>https://upittpress.org/books/9780822963172/</ref> Her second collection, ''Darwin\u2019s Mother'', published in 2017 also by [[University of Pittsburgh Press]], is an exploration of evolution, natural science, and humanity\u2019s place in the world<ref>https://upittpress.org/books/9780822965169/</ref>, and was a finalist for the 2018 Ohioana Library Association Book Award for Poetry<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohioana.org/ohioana-announces-2018-book-award-finalists/|title=Ohioana Announces 2018 Book Award Finalists \u2013 Ohioana Library}}</ref>. \n\nNordgren is the recipient of two fellowships from the [[Fine Arts Work Center]] in Provincetown, MA,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.fawc.org/all-fellows|title=All Fellows|date=January 9, 2014|website=FINE ARTS WORK CENTER in Provincetown}}</ref> as well as an Individual Excellence Award from the [[Ohio Arts Council]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> She has also received scholarships from the [[Bread Loaf Writers\u2019 Conference]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://memoriousmag.wordpress.com/2014/11/19/poetry-spotlight-contributor-sarah-rose-nordgren/|title=Poetry Spotlight: Contributor Sarah Rose Nordgren|date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> a fellowship from the [[Sewanee Writers' Conference]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sewaneewriters.org/right-here/sewanee-writers.php|title=Sewanee Writers' Conference \u2022 Right Here \u2022 The University of the South|website=www.sewaneewriters.org}}</ref> and residencies at the [[Vermont Studio Center]] and [[Virginia Center for the Creative Arts]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> She won the 2012 James Wright Poetry Award from [[Mid-American Review]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://casit.bgsu.edu/midamericanreview/volume-xxxiii-no-1/|title=Volume XXXIII, no. 1 \u2013 Mid-American Review}}</ref> \n\nNordgren also creates video and performance art with dance and video maker Kathleen Kelley under the name Smart Snow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sarahrosenordgren.com/smart-snow/|title=Smart Snow}}</ref> Their performance installation, Digitized Figures, was produced at the Gowanus Lofts in Brooklyn, NY in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dance-enthusiast.com/dance-listings/events/view/Digitized-Figures-by-Smart-Snow-2016-10-14_23|title=\"Digitized Figures\" by Smart Snow|website=www.dance-enthusiast.com}}</ref> \u201cTerritory,\u201d a poetry and dance video, was published by [[TriQuarterly Magazine]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.triquarterly.org/issues/issue-153/territory|title=Territory|website=TriQuarterly}}</ref>\n\nNordgren is an Associate Editor for the journal [[32 Poems]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://32poems.com/masthead/|title=Masthead &#124; 32 Poems Magazine}}</ref> She lives in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/conversation-poet-sarah-rose-nordgren|title=A conversation with poet Sarah Rose Nordgren|first=Barbara|last=Gray|website=www.wvxu.org}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*''Best Bones'', ([[University of Pittsburgh Press]], 2014)\n*''Darwin\u2019s Mother'', ([[University of Pittsburgh Press]], 2017)\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Agnes Lynch Starrett Poetry Prize]], ''Best Bones'', 2013\n*James Wright Poetry Prize from [[Mid-American Review]], 2012<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://sarahrosenordgren.com Official Site]\n* [https://upittpress.org/authors/sarah-rose-nordgren/ University of Pittsburgh Press - Author Page]\n* [https://museumofnonvisibleart.com/interviews/sarah-rose-nordgren/ Interview: Yale Radio WYBC]\n* [http://www.essaydaily.org/2017/05/smart-snow-intermedia-collaborations-of.html Interview: Essay Daily]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160325101641/http://wvxu.org/post/conversation-poet-sarah-rose-nordgren Interview: WVXU Cincinnati]\n* [https://memoriousmag.wordpress.com/2014/11/19/poetry-spotlight-contributor-sarah-rose-nordgren/ Interview: Memorious Magazine]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nordgren, Sarah Rose}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Greensboro alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name               = Sarah Rose Nordgren\n| occupation         = Poet\n| education          = [[Sarah Lawrence College]]<br>[[University of North Carolina at Greensboro]]<br>[[University of Cincinnati]]\n| awards             = [[Agnes Lynch Starrett Poetry Prize]]<br>James Wright Poetry Prize\n| website            =  {{URL|sarahrosenordgren.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Sarah Rose Nordgren''' is an American poet. She is the author of ''Darwin\u2019s Mother'', and of ''Best Bones'', winner of the [[Agnes Lynch Starrett Poetry Prize|Agnes Lynch Starrett Prize]] in 2013. \n\n==Early life and education==\nSarah Rose Nordgren was raised in [[Durham, North Carolina]]. She has a BA in Liberal Arts from [[Sarah Lawrence College]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sarahlawrence.edu/alumni/news/2016-08-26-sarah-rose-nordgren-04.html|title=Sarah Rose Nordgren \u201904|website=www.sarahlawrence.edu}}</ref>, an MFA in Poetry from The [[University of North Carolina at Greensboro]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mfagreensboro.org/alumni/sarah-rose-nordgren/|title=Sarah Rose Nordgren - UNCG &#124; Creative WritingUNCG &#124; Creative Writing|first1=A. Call To|last1=Writers|first2=A. Call To|last2=Alumni}}</ref> where she held the [[Fred Chappell]] Fellowship<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theparisamerican.com/poetry173.html|title=The Cell by Sarah Rose Nordgren|website=www.theparisamerican.com}}</ref>, and a PhD in English and Creative Writing from the [[University of Cincinnati]], with a Graduate Certificate in Women\u2019s, Gender, and Sexuality Studies<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=http://sarahrosenordgren.com/sarah-rose-nordgren-bio/|title=Sarah Rose Nordgren Bio &#124; Sara Rose Nordgren}}</ref>, where she was also a Taft Summer Research Fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://multisite.uc.edu/taft/fellowship/graduate-summer-fellows|title=Graduate Summer Fellows|website=multisite.uc.edu}}</ref> and a Ricking Dissertation Fellow.\n\n==Career==\nNordgren\u2019s first poetry collection, ''Best Bones'', was published in 2014 by [[University of Pittsburgh Press]]. The collection, with themes of myth, identity, domestic life, and loss, won the prestigious 2013 [[Agnes Lynch Starrett Poetry Prize|Agnes Lynch Starrett Prize]] for a first book.<ref>https://upittpress.org/books/9780822963172/</ref> Her second collection, ''Darwin\u2019s Mother'', published in 2017 also by [[University of Pittsburgh Press]], is an exploration of evolution, natural science, and humanity\u2019s place in the world<ref>https://upittpress.org/books/9780822965169/</ref>, and was a finalist for the 2018 Ohioana Library Association Book Award for Poetry<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohioana.org/ohioana-announces-2018-book-award-finalists/|title=Ohioana Announces 2018 Book Award Finalists \u2013 Ohioana Library}}</ref>. \n\nNordgren is the recipient of two fellowships from the [[Fine Arts Work Center]] in Provincetown, MA,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.fawc.org/all-fellows|title=All Fellows|date=January 9, 2014|website=FINE ARTS WORK CENTER in Provincetown}}</ref> as well as an Individual Excellence Award from the [[Ohio Arts Council]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> She has also received scholarships from the [[Bread Loaf Writers\u2019 Conference]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://memoriousmag.wordpress.com/2014/11/19/poetry-spotlight-contributor-sarah-rose-nordgren/|title=Poetry Spotlight: Contributor Sarah Rose Nordgren|date=November 19, 2014}}</ref> a fellowship from the [[Sewanee Writers' Conference]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sewaneewriters.org/right-here/sewanee-writers.php|title=Sewanee Writers' Conference \u2022 Right Here \u2022 The University of the South|website=www.sewaneewriters.org}}</ref> and residencies at the [[Vermont Studio Center]] and [[Virginia Center for the Creative Arts]].<ref name=\"auto1\"/> She won the 2012 James Wright Poetry Award from [[Mid-American Review]].<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://casit.bgsu.edu/midamericanreview/volume-xxxiii-no-1/|title=Volume XXXIII, no. 1 \u2013 Mid-American Review}}</ref> \n\nNordgren also creates video and performance art with dance and video maker Kathleen Kelley under the name Smart Snow.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sarahrosenordgren.com/smart-snow/|title=Smart Snow}}</ref> Their performance installation, Digitized Figures, was produced at the Gowanus Lofts in Brooklyn, NY in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dance-enthusiast.com/dance-listings/events/view/Digitized-Figures-by-Smart-Snow-2016-10-14_23|title=\"Digitized Figures\" by Smart Snow|website=www.dance-enthusiast.com}}</ref> \u201cTerritory,\u201d a poetry and dance video, was published by [[TriQuarterly Magazine]] in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.triquarterly.org/issues/issue-153/territory|title=Territory|website=TriQuarterly}}</ref>\n\nNordgren is an Associate Editor for the journal [[32 Poems]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://32poems.com/masthead/|title=Masthead &#124; 32 Poems Magazine}}</ref> She lives in [[Cincinnati, Ohio]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wvxu.org/post/conversation-poet-sarah-rose-nordgren|title=A conversation with poet Sarah Rose Nordgren|first=Barbara|last=Gray|website=www.wvxu.org}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*''Best Bones'', ([[University of Pittsburgh Press]], 2014)\n*''Darwin\u2019s Mother'', ([[University of Pittsburgh Press]], 2017)\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Agnes Lynch Starrett Poetry Prize]], ''Best Bones'', 2013\n*James Wright Poetry Prize from [[Mid-American Review]], 2012<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n* [http://sarahrosenordgren.com Official Site]\n* [https://upittpress.org/authors/sarah-rose-nordgren/ University of Pittsburgh Press - Author Page]\n* [https://museumofnonvisibleart.com/interviews/sarah-rose-nordgren/ Interview: Yale Radio WYBC]\n* [http://www.essaydaily.org/2017/05/smart-snow-intermedia-collaborations-of.html Interview: Essay Daily]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20160325101641/http://wvxu.org/post/conversation-poet-sarah-rose-nordgren Interview: WVXU Cincinnati]\n* [https://memoriousmag.wordpress.com/2014/11/19/poetry-spotlight-contributor-sarah-rose-nordgren/ Interview: Memorious Magazine]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Nordgren, Sarah Rose}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women writers]]\n[[Category:Sarah Lawrence College alumni]]\n[[Category:University of North Carolina at Greensboro alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Cincinnati alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Section heading change: External Links \u2192 External links using ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sarah_Rose_Nordgren"}
{"title_page": "Yungas manakin", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| image = Yungas Manakin (Chiroxiphia boliviana).jpg\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22701080/0 |title=''Chiroxiphia boliviana'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Chiroxiphia\n| species = boliviana\n| authority = [[Joel Asaph Allen|Allen]], 1889\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''Yungas manakin''' (''Chiroxiphia boliviana'') is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Pipridae]]. It closely resembles the [[blue-backed manakin]], but unlike that species it has dull dark red legs and is found in humid highland forests in the [[Yungas]] of southeastern [[Peru]] and [[Bolivia]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!-- BulletinOfTheBritishOrnithologistsClub127:49. -->\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q841119}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:manakin, Yungas}}\n[[Category:Chiroxiphia|Yungas manakin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Yungas]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1889|Yungas manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Pipridae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| status = LC\n| image = Yungas Manakin (Chiroxiphia boliviana).jpg\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22701080/0 |title=''Chiroxiphia boliviana'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Chiroxiphia\n| species = boliviana\n| authority = [[Joel Asaph Allen|Allen]], 1889\n| synonyms = \n}}\n\nThe '''Yungas manakin''' (''Chiroxiphia boliviana'') is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Pipridae]] family. It closely resembles the [[blue-backed manakin]], but unlike that species it has dull dark red legs and is found in humid highland forests in the [[Yungas]] of southeastern [[Peru]] and [[Bolivia]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!-- BulletinOfTheBritishOrnithologistsClub127:49. -->\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q841119}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:manakin, Yungas}}\n[[Category:Chiroxiphia|Yungas manakin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Yungas]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1889|Yungas manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Pipridae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yungas_manakin"}
{"title_page": "WAPAL", "text_new": "{{Infobox_gene}}\n'''Wings apart-like protein homolog''' ('''WAPL''') is a [[protein]] that in humans is encoded by the ''WAPAL'' [[gene]].<ref name=\"pmid9039502\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Nagase T, Seki N, Ishikawa K, Ohira M, Kawarabayasi Y, Ohara O, Tanaka A, Kotani H, Miyajima N, Nomura N | display-authors = 6 | title = Prediction of the coding sequences of unidentified human genes. VI. The coding sequences of 80 new genes (KIAA0201-KIAA0280) deduced by analysis of cDNA clones from cell line KG-1 and brain | journal = DNA Research | volume = 3 | issue = 5 | pages = 321\u20139, 341-54 | date = October 1996 | pmid = 9039502 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1093/dnares/3.5.321 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17112726\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gandhi R, Gillespie PJ, Hirano T | title = Human Wapl is a cohesin-binding protein that promotes sister-chromatid resolution in mitotic prophase | journal = Current Biology | volume = 16 | issue = 24 | pages = 2406\u201317 | date = December 2006 | pmid = 17112726 | pmc = 1850625 | doi = 10.1016/j.cub.2006.10.061 }}</ref><ref name=\"entrez\">{{cite web | title = Entrez Gene: WAPAL wings apart-like homolog (Drosophila)| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?Db=gene&Cmd=ShowDetailView&TermToSearch=23063| access-date = }}</ref> WAPL is a key regulator of the [[Cohesin]] complex which mediates [[Establishment of sister chromatid cohesion|sister chromatid cohesion]], homologous recombination and [[Topologically associating domain|DNA looping]]. Cohesin is formed of [[SMC3]], [[SMC1A|SMC1]], [[RAD21]] and either [[STAG1|SA1]] or [[STAG2|SA2]].  <ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Yatskevich S, Rhodes J, Nasmyth K | title = Organization of Chromosomal DNA by SMC Complexes | journal = Annual Review of Genetics | volume = 53 | pages = 445\u2013482 | date = December 2019 | pmid = 31577909 | doi = 10.1146/annurev-genet-112618-043633 }}</ref> Cohesin has a ring-like arrangement and it is thought that it associates with the chromosome by entrapping it whether as a loop of DNA, a single strand or a pair of sister chromosomes. WAPL forms a complex with [[PDS5A]] or [[PDS5B]] and releases cohesin from DNA by opening the interface between SMC3 and RAD21.\n\n== Interphase ==\n[[File:Structure of PDS5B (blue), WAPL (green) and IP6 (PDB 5HDT) (Ouyang et al., 2016).png|thumb|left|Structure of PDS5B (blue), WAPL (green) and IP6 (PDB 5HDT) (Ouyang et al., 2016)]]\nCohesin loading begins in telophase and is mediated by [[NIPBL]] and its binding partner MAU2. In [[Cell cycle|G1]], WAPL forms a complex with PDS5 and removes cohesin from the DNA but it is reloaded by NIPBL-MAU2. The equilibrium between loading and release give cohesin a DNA residence time of 20 minutes. During DNA replication, a fraction of cohesin is acetylated and binds to [[CDCA5|Sororin]] making it resistant to WAPL and able to hold sister chromatids together. This is crucial for the maintenance of sister chromatid cohesion because onse the sister chromatids are separated, cohesion cannot be reestablished.\n\n== Prophase pathway ==\nWhen a cell enters mitosis, Sororin is phosphorylated causing it to dissociate from cohesin meaning WAPL can remove cohesin from the DNA. A complex of [[SGOL1]] and [[Protein phosphatase 2|PP2A]] dephosphorylates cohesin at the centromere protecting it from WAPL-mediated release. Sister chromatid cohesion is therefore maintained at the centromeres where it is required for mitosis but lost on the arms. This removal of cohesin is known as the Prophase Pathway and results in the X-shape sister chromatids observed in chromosome spreads.\n\n== Mechanism ==\nWAPL release cohesin from DNA by opening the SMC3-RAD21 interface thereby allowing DNA to pass out of the ring.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beckou\u00ebt F, Srinivasan M, Roig MB, Chan KL, Scheinost JC, Batty P, Hu B, Petela N, Gligoris T, Smith AC, Strmecki L, Rowland BD, Nasmyth K | display-authors = 6 | title = Releasing Activity Disengages Cohesin's Smc3/Scc1 Interface in a Process Blocked by Acetylation | journal = Molecular Cell | volume = 61 | issue = 4 | pages = 563\u2013574 | date = February 2016 | pmid = 26895425 | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2016.01.026 | pmc = 4769318 }}</ref> Opening of this interface is regulated by ATP-binding by the SMC subunits. This causes the ATPase head domains to dimerise and deforms the coiled coil of SMC3 therefore disrupting the binding of RAD21 to the coiled coil.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Muir KW, Li Y, Weis F, Panne D | title = The structure of the cohesin ATPase elucidates the mechanism of SMC-kleisin ring opening | journal = Nature Structural & Molecular Biology | volume = 27 | issue = 3 | pages = 233\u2013239 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32066964 | doi = 10.1038/s41594-020-0379-7 | pmc = 7100847 }}</ref> It is not known how WAPL regulates the process of ATP binding.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{gene-10-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox_gene}}\n'''Wings apart-like protein homolog''' ('''WAPL''') is a [[protein]] that in humans is encoded by the ''WAPAL'' [[gene]].<ref name=\"pmid9039502\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Nagase T, Seki N, Ishikawa K, Ohira M, Kawarabayasi Y, Ohara O, Tanaka A, Kotani H, Miyajima N, Nomura N | display-authors = 6 | title = Prediction of the coding sequences of unidentified human genes. VI. The coding sequences of 80 new genes (KIAA0201-KIAA0280) deduced by analysis of cDNA clones from cell line KG-1 and brain | journal = DNA Research | volume = 3 | issue = 5 | pages = 321\u20139, 341-54 | date = October 1996 | pmid = 9039502 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1093/dnares/3.5.321 }}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17112726\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Gandhi R, Gillespie PJ, Hirano T | title = Human Wapl is a cohesin-binding protein that promotes sister-chromatid resolution in mitotic prophase | journal = Current Biology | volume = 16 | issue = 24 | pages = 2406\u201317 | date = December 2006 | pmid = 17112726 | pmc = 1850625 | doi = 10.1016/j.cub.2006.10.061 }}</ref><ref name=\"entrez\">{{cite web | title = Entrez Gene: WAPAL wings apart-like homolog (Drosophila)| url = https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/sites/entrez?Db=gene&Cmd=ShowDetailView&TermToSearch=23063| access-date = }}</ref> WAPL is a key regulator of the [[Cohesin]] complex which mediates [[Establishment of sister chromatid cohesion|sister chromatid cohesion]], homologous recombination and [[Topologically associating domain|DNA looping]]. Cohesin is formed of [[SMC3]], [[SMC1A|SMC1]], [[RAD21]] and either [[STAG1|SA1]] or [[STAG2|SA2]].  <ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Yatskevich S, Rhodes J, Nasmyth K | title = Organization of Chromosomal DNA by SMC Complexes | journal = Annual Review of Genetics | volume = 53 | pages = 445\u2013482 | date = December 2019 | pmid = 31577909 | doi = 10.1146/annurev-genet-112618-043633 }}</ref> Cohesin has a ring-like arrangement and it is thought that it associates with the chromosome by entrapping it whether as a loop of DNA, a single strand or a pair of sister chromosomes. WAPL forms a complex with [[PDS5A]] or [[PDS5B]] and releases cohesin from DNA by opening the interface between SMC3 and RAD21.\n\n== Interphase ==\n[[File:Structure of PDS5B (blue), WAPL (green) and IP6 (PDB 5HDT) (Ouyang et al., 2016).png|thumb|left|Structure of PDS5B (blue), WAPL (green) and IP6 (PDB 5HDT) (Ouyang et al., 2016)]]\nCohesin loading begins in telophase and is mediated by [[NIPBL]] and its binding partner MAU2. In [[Cell cycle|G1]], WAPL removes cohesin from the DNA but it is reloaded by NIPBL-MAU2. The equilibrium between loading and release give cohesin a DNA residence time of 20 minutes. When DNA is replicated, a fraction of cohesin is acetylated and binds to [[CDCA5|Sororin]] making it resistant to WAPL and able to hold sister chromatids together. This is crucial for the maintenance of sister chromatid cohesion because onse the sister chromatids are separated, cohesion cannot be reestablished.\n\n== Prophase pathway ==\nWhen a cell enters mitosis, Sororin is phosphorylated causing it to dissociate from cohesin meaning WAPL can remove cohesin from the DNA. A complex of [[SGOL1]] and [[Protein phosphatase 2|PP2A]] dephosphorylates cohesin at the centromere protecting it from WAPL-mediated release. Sister chromatid cohesion is therefore maintained at the centromeres where it is required for mitosis but lost on the arms. This removal of cohesin is known as the Prophase Pathway and results in the X-shape sister chromatids observed in chromosome spreads.\n\n== Mechanism ==\nWAPL release cohesin from DNA by opening the SMC3-RAD21 interface thereby allowing DNA to pass out of the ring.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Beckou\u00ebt F, Srinivasan M, Roig MB, Chan KL, Scheinost JC, Batty P, Hu B, Petela N, Gligoris T, Smith AC, Strmecki L, Rowland BD, Nasmyth K | display-authors = 6 | title = Releasing Activity Disengages Cohesin's Smc3/Scc1 Interface in a Process Blocked by Acetylation | journal = Molecular Cell | volume = 61 | issue = 4 | pages = 563\u2013574 | date = February 2016 | pmid = 26895425 | doi = 10.1016/j.molcel.2016.01.026 | pmc = 4769318 }}</ref> Opening of this interface is regulated by ATP-binding by the SMC subunits. This causes the ATPase head domains to dimerise and deforms the coiled coil of SMC3 therefore disrupting the binding of RAD21 to the coiled coil.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Muir KW, Li Y, Weis F, Panne D | title = The structure of the cohesin ATPase elucidates the mechanism of SMC-kleisin ring opening | journal = Nature Structural & Molecular Biology | volume = 27 | issue = 3 | pages = 233\u2013239 | date = March 2020 | pmid = 32066964 | doi = 10.1038/s41594-020-0379-7 | pmc = 7100847 }}</ref> It is not known how WAPL regulates the process of ATP binding.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{gene-10-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Jimcricket90", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInterphase", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WAPAL"}
{"title_page": "Orange-bellied manakin", "text_new": "{{speciesbox\n| image = PipraSuavissimaKeulemans.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22701020/0 |title=''Lepidothrix suavissima'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Lepidothrix\n| species = suavissima\n| authority = ([[Osbert Salvin|Salvin]] & [[Frederick DuCane Godman|Godman]], 1882)\n| synonyms = \n''Pipra suavissima'' <small>Salvin & Godman, 1882</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''orange-bellied manakin''' (''Lepidothrix suavissima''), also known as the '''tepui manakin''',<ref name = \"Ridgely\"/> is a species of [[bird]] in the family [[Pipridae]]. It resembles and is closely related to the [[white-fronted manakin]] (''L. serena''), and the two were formerly considered [[conspecific]].\n\nIt is, as suggested by its alternative [[common name]], restricted to humid forest growing on the [[tepui]]s in southern [[Venezuela]], far northern [[Brazil]], and central [[Guyana]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | refs = \n<ref name = \"Ridgely\">{{cite book | title = The Birds of South America: Vol. II, The Suboscine Passerines | first = Robert S. | last = Ridgely | first2 = Guy | last2 = Tudor | year = 1994 | publisher = University of Texas Press | location = Austin, TX, USA | isbn = 0-292-77063-4 | page = 721 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_y4FMhURra0C&pg=PA721 }}</ref>\n\n}}<!-- BulletinOfTheBritishOrnithologistsClub127:118. -->\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q282476}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:manakin, orange-bellied}}\n[[Category:Lepidothrix|orange-bellied manakin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Guianas]]\n[[Category:Birds of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1882|orange-bellied manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Pipridae-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{speciesbox\n| image = PipraSuavissimaKeulemans.jpg\n| status = LC\n| status_system = IUCN3.1\n| status_ref = <ref>{{cite iucn|url=https://www.iucnredlist.org/details/22701020/0 |title=''Lepidothrix suavissima'' |author=BirdLife International |author-link=BirdLife International |year=2012 |access-date=26 November 2013|ref=harv}}</ref>\n| genus = Lepidothrix\n| species = suavissima\n| authority = ([[Osbert Salvin|Salvin]] & [[Frederick DuCane Godman|Godman]], 1882)\n| synonyms = \n''Pipra suavissima'' <small>Salvin & Godman, 1882</small>\n}}\n\nThe '''orange-bellied manakin''' (''Lepidothrix suavissima''), also known as the '''tepui manakin''',<ref name = \"Ridgely\"/> is a species of [[bird]] in the [[Pipridae]] family. It resembles and is closely related to the [[white-fronted manakin]] (''L. serena''), and the two were formerly considered [[conspecific]].\n\nIt is, as suggested by its alternative [[common name]], restricted to humid forest growing on the [[tepui]]s in southern [[Venezuela]], far northern [[Brazil]], and central [[Guyana]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist | refs = \n<ref name = \"Ridgely\">{{cite book | title = The Birds of South America: Vol. II, The Suboscine Passerines | first = Robert S. | last = Ridgely | first2 = Guy | last2 = Tudor | year = 1994 | publisher = University of Texas Press | location = Austin, TX, USA | isbn = 0-292-77063-4 | page = 721 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=_y4FMhURra0C&pg=PA721 }}</ref>\n\n}}<!-- BulletinOfTheBritishOrnithologistsClub127:118. -->\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q282476}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:manakin, orange-bellied}}\n[[Category:Lepidothrix|orange-bellied manakin]]\n[[Category:Birds of the Guianas]]\n[[Category:Birds of Venezuela]]\n[[Category:Birds described in 1882|orange-bellied manakin]]\n[[Category:Taxonomy articles created by Polbot]]\n\n\n{{Pipridae-stub}}\n", "name_user": "WolfmanSF", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orange-bellied_manakin"}
